INSERT INTO `cmsplugin_blog_entrytitle` VALUES (1,1,'en','OUR PLANT...','our-plant','blog/Gin_Still_Condenser_for_blog.jpg','Our main suppliers have been busy moving forward with fabricating our distillery plant, all ready to start installation on site in the spring. One of our suppliers is Musk, based near Burton on Trent, the brewing centre of the UK. They have tremendous expertise in brewing plant, and we are introducing these very high brewery standards into our distillery plant -...','<hr />\r\n<p>Our main suppliers have been busy moving forward with fabricating our distillery plant, all ready to start installation on site in the spring.</p>\r\n<p>One of our suppliers is Musk, based near Burton on Trent, the brewing centre of the UK. They have tremendous expertise in brewing plant, and we are introducing these very high brewery standards into our distillery plant - for our mashtun and washbacks. &nbsp;We are sure that this will make a difference to our final spirit, to improve its quality yet further.</p>\r\n<p>The three stills (two for the malt whisky one for gin and vodka - yes, we are going to produce a vodka as well) are being made by McMillans based near Edinburgh. &nbsp;They have a long history of making stills for the whisky industry, and ours will be beautifully crafted to our own unique design. &nbsp;Our Master Distiller, Chris Anderson, recently visited to see how they are progressing - and these are some photos of the stills and condensers as they are being made. &nbsp;Exciting times!</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.lakesdistillery.com/gallery\">Click here for photos!</a></p>',7),(2,2,'en',' THE ONE HAS CONTINUED TO RECEIVE A TREMENDOUS RESPONSE.....','one-has-continued-receive-tremendous-response','blog/IMG_0247-2.jpg','It\'s been another busy few weeks for us at The Lakes Distillery.  Our new blend, The ONE,  has continued to receive a tremendous response - you can see some of the reviews here: http://www.liv...','<p><span class=\"creation_date\">It\'s been another busy few weeks for us at The Lakes Distillery. &nbsp;Our new blend, The ONE, &nbsp;has continued to receive a tremendous response - you can see some of the reviews here:</span></p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.livingroomwhisky.com/project/the-one-the-lakes-distillery/\">http://www.livingroomwhisky.com/project/the-one-the-lakes-distillery/</a></p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://whiskyisrael.co.il/2013/11/08/the-one-british-blend-lakes-distillery/\">http://whiskyisrael.co.il/2013/11/08/the-one-british-blend-lakes-distillery/</a></p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.somersetwhisky.com/index.php/review-the-one-british-blended-whisky/\">http://www.somersetwhisky.com/index.php/review-the-one-british-blended-whisky/</a></p>\r\n<p><span>You can buy The ONE through our&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.lakesdistillery.com/shop\">website shop</a>, and soon it will also be available in some other European markets. &nbsp;I have been hopping on to planes and trains over the last few weeks, and we are set to launch very soon in France and the Netherlands - and we hope in Russia in 2014. &nbsp;The response to The ONE has been just as positive in these markets.</span></p>\r\n<p><span>We have also been developing our label design and packaging for&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.lakesdistillery.com/brands/the-lakes-gin\">The Lakes Gin</a>&nbsp;that we will launch next spring - it looks great! &nbsp;This will be the only gin to be distilled in the Lake District, in our own still at the distillery. &nbsp;And -&nbsp;<span>latest news</span>&nbsp;- we are now planning to produce The Lakes Vodka, using the same still as we will use for gin, and the same ideal water from the river Derwent. &nbsp;So with whisky, gin and vodka we hope to keep everybody happy!</span></p>\r\n<p><span>We are also making good progress on our plant. &nbsp;Musk, who are supplying our mashtun and washbacks, are moving ahead with the fabrication, and McMillans are also progressing we</span></p>',7),(3,3,'en','THE USA AND CRAFT DISTILLING BY GAVIN D SMITH','usa-and-craft-distilling-gavin-d-smith','blog/20091028-whiskey-istock.jpg','Whisky is now made in more countries around the world than ever before, with craft/boutique/micro/artisanal  take your pick of terms  distilleries operated by passionate and committed individuals and groups from The Netherlands to New Zealand, Sweden to South Africa. There is even going to be one in the English Lakes before too long!\r\n','<p><span class=\"creation_date\">Whisky is now made in more countries around the world than ever before, with craft/boutique/micro/artisanal &ndash; take your pick of terms &ndash; distilleries operated by passionate and committed individuals and groups from The Netherlands to New Zealand, Sweden to South Africa. There is even going to be one in the English Lakes before too long!</span></p>\r\n<p>However, the greatest growth in spirit craft distilling has undoubtedly taken place in the USA, where the Kentucky and Tennessee old guard of Buffalo Trace, Heaven Hill, Jim Beam, Jack Daniels and their like are being taken on by a new breed of distiller, keen to experiment and innovate and extend the category of &lsquo;American whiskey&rsquo; way beyond anywhere it has been before.</p>\r\n<p>Firstly, some figures. According to the American Distilling Institute (ADI), which describes itself as &ldquo;The voice of artisan distilling,&rdquo; in 2003 there were 69 craft distilleries in the USA. That number has now risen to more than 400, and it is estimated by ADI that the number will grow to between 600 and 800 by then end of 2015. Although there is no legal definition, a &lsquo;craft&rsquo; distillery is usually considered to be one that produces less than 100,000 gallons of spirits in a year.</p>\r\n<p>Obviously not all of them make whiskey, with white spirits being favoured by many due to the fact that they do not require ageing, unlike whiskey, and thereby produce a much faster potential return on production costs. But at some point, most craft distillers do get to lay down some spirit to mature as whiskey, though there has also been a trend to offer unaged &lsquo;white&rsquo; corn whiskey, such as Popcorn Sutton\'s Tennessee White Whiskey and the West Virginia Distillery Company&rsquo;s (entirely legal) &nbsp;Mountain Moonshine.</p>\r\n<p>On the subject of the law, one major event which changed the landscape of US distilling forever was the period of Prohibition, which lasted from 1920 to 1933 and made the production and consumption of alcohol illegal in the USA. Not surprisingly, the ban decimated the whiskey-distilling landscape of the USA. In Kentucky alone, of the 17 operational distilleries before Prohibition, only seven re-opened after repeal, and that picture was repeated across the States. A few decades later, amalgamations and rationalisation programmes put in place by a number of large distilling corporations led to the closure of even more distilleries.</p>\r\n<p>The positive events of the last decade or so &ndash; mirroring the way that the US craft brewing movement expanded so rapidly from the 1990s - have gone some way to restoring an independent whiskey-making tradition which offers individual craftsmanship and a wide stylistic choice of products.</p>\r\n<p>Back in 2005 Tuthilltown Spirits at Gardiner in the Hudson Valley opened for business, and began distilling what was remarkably the first Bourbon in New York State and the first legal pot-distilled whiskey to be made there since Prohibition.</p>\r\n<p>Co-founder Ralph Erenzo says &ldquo;We started by distilling vodka from apples, but began experimenting with grains right away, making corn whiskey. Our first aged spirit was an experiment that turned out quite well indeed. We also realised early that whiskey was coming back, in particular the interest in straightforward aged spirits; people are just tired of the same old thing. And we copied no one.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;We&rsquo;re not making whiskey the &lsquo;traditional&rsquo; way, as defined for 80 years by the big whiskey producers. We are making it the way their grandfathers made it. We do all the work, hands-on, from scratch in one building.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>Tuthilltown&rsquo;s range of products includes the popular Hudson Baby Bourbon, Four Grain Bourbon, Manhattan Rye and Single Malt whiskey, and the quality of the whiskey in question led high-profile Scottish distiller William Grant &amp; Sons Ltd to acquire the Hudson whiskeys range in 2010, giving the Glenfiddich distiller a foothold in the US craft distilling marketplace.</p>\r\n<p>Ralph Erenzo and colleagues are experimenting with grain types such as spelt, oats and rice, and the Tuthilltown warehouses resonate to the sound of loud drum-and-bass music, intended to aid the ageing process &ndash; they call it sonic maturation!</p>\r\n<p>Meanwhile, across in Montana, the state&rsquo;s first legal whiskey distillery &ndash; RoughStock &ndash; likes to mature its RoughStock Montana Malt Whiskey, Spring Wheat, Sweet Corn and Straight Rye to the sound of Johnny Cash, which is apparently the spirit&rsquo;s favourite country music.</p>\r\n<p>Experimentation is the name of the game for many of the new generation of craft distillers, though a significant number are also recreating American classics using tradition Bourbon and rye recipes. Few distilleries are more devoted to &lsquo;pushing the envelope&rsquo; than Balcones, founded by Chip Tate at Waco in Texas during 2008, and Corsair, established by Darek Bell a year previously in Nashville, Tennessee.</p>\r\n<p>Tate&rsquo;s enterprising nature led him to produce Brimstone, which infuses corn whiskey withsmke derived from wild Texas scrub oak. He also produces a spirit called Rumble &ndash; made with distilled Texas honey, distilled mission fig spirit and turbinado sugar, matured in American oak barrels!</p>\r\n<p>At the same time, DarekBell makes whiskey fromquinoa and pumpkin-spiced moonshine, as well as more traditional elements, and is the author of Alt Whiskeys, subtitled &lsquo;Alternative whiskeys and techniques for the adventurous distiller.&rsquo; He declares that &ldquo;For a long time, all of the products coming out of the bigger boys were very much the same. All of a sudden, they\'re changing quite a bit too, and I think that\'s definitely attributable to the craft distillers.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>With a broader choice being offered by many of the major commercial distillers and an apparently never-ending stream of new products emanating from small-scale enterprises, there has probably never been a more exciting time for American whiskey.</p>',7),(4,4,'en','WELL, WE HAVE HAD A VERY EXCITING FEW WEEKS!','well-we-have-had-very-exciting-few-weeks','blog/The-One-Launch.gif','The highlight undoubtedly has been the launch of our new blended whisky, The ONE , which has been incredibly well received.  It all started at the Taste Cumbria Festival at the end of September, with a launch even...','<p><span class=\"creation_date\">The highlight undoubtedly has been the launch of our new blended whisky,&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.lakesdistillery.com/brands/brand-x\">The ONE</a>, which has been incredibly well received.&nbsp; It all started at the Taste Cumbria Festival at the end of September, with a launch event at The Trout in Cockermouth, and then our sales launch at a stand at the festival.&nbsp; Our sales were way above what we anticipated &ndash; at least 10 times, and the reaction to The ONE was so positive, both in the packaging and the taste.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span>We have made a huge effort over the last months to ensure&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.lakesdistillery.com/brands/brand-x\">The ONE</a>&nbsp;was as perfect as we could make it.&nbsp; The blend is the first blend of British whiskies (as opposed to being only scotch), and it has been carefully and lovingly crafted by us to create what is an outstanding whisky.&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.lakesdistillery.com/our%20people/our-distillery/our-people/alan-rutherford\">Alan Rutherford</a>, who is on our board and whose expertise is second to none, has played a central role in this, and we are delighted with the result.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span>The packaging has also had a very positive reaction.&nbsp; The leading Newcastle based design agency, Hedley McEwan, developed the design, and it really is something different in the whisky market.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span>Sales through our website have started very well, and we are now talking to partners in other markets to launch.&nbsp; So the future looks very bright for&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.lakesdistillery.com/brands/brand-x\">The ONE</a>.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span>Have you tried it yet?&nbsp; If you have, please do let me know what you think.</span></p>',7),(5,5,'en','MY FIRST Post ON OUR BEAUTIFUL NEW WEBSITE','my-first-post-our-beautiful-new-website','blog/Paul_Currie_Lakes_Distillery.JPG','So here it is  my first post on our beautiful new website.  I will regularly put fingers to keyboard and let you know the latest news about the distillery, and my current thoughts on the whisky and gin world.  I hope you find them entertaining! It has been a long ro...','<p><span class=\"creation_date\">So here it is &ndash; my first post on our beautiful new website. &nbsp;I will regularly put fingers to keyboard and let you know the latest news about the distillery, and my current thoughts on the whisky and gin world.&nbsp; I hope you find them entertaining!</span></p>\r\n<p>It has been a long road to make our dream of The Lakes Distillery become reality, but we are now very much on the home stretch.&nbsp; I did know before starting how many hurdles would need to be jumped, so I can&rsquo;t claim to have been surprised. But it nevertheless has been quite a challenge.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Finding a suitable site was the key task, and we really have come up trumps with our site at Bassenthwaite.&nbsp; Do look through the various photos on our website and on our Facebook page &ndash; it really is as beautiful as it looks!&nbsp; The Victorian Model Farm where we are based is itself a gem &ndash; even without renovation it exudes history and character.&nbsp; If we had built it from scratch, it would not have been much different, as each building lends itself perfectly to our use &ndash; the wonderful barn that will be the distillery, the old byre that will be the bistro.&nbsp; Our setting so near the river Derwent, which will provide ideal water for our whisky and gin, is perfect &ndash; and we are only a few hundred metres from the only lake in the Lake District, Bassenthwaite, with Skiddaw towering above.</p>\r\n<p>Work on the plant has been progressing well, with everything now ordered &ndash; our stills from McMillans in Scotland, the rest of the plant from Musks near Burton on Trent.&nbsp; Musks have a tremendous reputation in supplying brewery plant, and we are sure that by using the latest brewing technology and plant we will produce an even better whisky.&nbsp; Our Master Distiller, Chris Anderson, has been very busy fine tuning every detail of the plant and design &ndash; this will be one of the best designed distilleries that has ever been set up!&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Our electricity supply is going in at the moment, so we will have a gleaming new substation ready to use in the next few weeks.&nbsp; Apologies to our neighbours who have had to put up with a traffic light system because of this work &ndash; thank you for your understanding!</p>\r\n<p>So exciting times lie ahead of us.&nbsp; Next year The Lakes Distillery will start production and our Visitor Centre will open.&nbsp; We can&rsquo;t wait.</p>',7),(6,6,'en','Work Is Underway On Stills For Lakes Distillery','work-underway','blog/New__Star.jpg','Monday, 16th December 2013 ','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>CRAFTSMEN have started making copper stills for the new Lakes Distillery, and construction work on site is due to begin in January.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Made to measure: A craftsman at specialist fabricator McMilllan, near Edinburgh, at work on one of the new stills (Main pic)</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span><img style=\"vertical-align: text-top; margin: 5px;\" src=\"/media/files/wash_still_head.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"544\" height=\"428\" />A consortium of private investors led by Paul Currie, a co-founder of the Isle of Arran Distillery, is converting a Victorian farm at Setmurthy, near Bassenthwaite, into a &pound;2.5m distillery.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The aim is to start production of <a href=\"/brands/lakes-malt/\">malt whisky</a>,&nbsp;<a href=\"/brands/lakes-gin/\">gin</a>&nbsp;and vodka by the spring of 2014.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Three copper stills &ndash; in which the spirits will be distilled &ndash; are being produced to a unique design by McMillan, a specialist fabricator at Prestonpans near Edinburgh.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>The company has been supplying stills to the Scottish whisky industry for more than 100 years.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Other plant and equipment is coming from Musk, of Burton-on-Trent, which has a long track record of working with breweries.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Mr Currie said: &ldquo;We have taken great care to find suppliers who are the very best in their field and this will ultimately be evident in the quality of the spirits we produce &ndash; they will be exceptional.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>&ldquo;Work to develop the distillery site will commence in January and we are well on schedule to start distilling Cumbria&rsquo;s first malt whisky for more than 100 years. We&rsquo;ve also been busy installing webcams so that people can view our progress.&rdquo;</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>The project includes a visitor centre with bar, bistro and shop. Production is expected to reach 300,000 bottles a year &ndash; although the distillery will have the capacity to produce 1m bottles &ndash; and the site should support 27 jobs.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Although production has yet to start, the Lakes Distillery launched its first whisky at the Taste Cumbria food event in Cockermouth in September.&nbsp;<a href=\"/brands/the-one\">The One</a>&nbsp;is a blend of grain and malt whiskies from other British distilleries. The distillery has also launched an exclusive&nbsp;<a href=\"/members/founders-club\">founders&rsquo; club</a>&nbsp;for whisky enthusiasts, limited to 2,975 members.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>They will receive one 70cl bottle each year for the first 10 years, starting in 2015, drawn from the distillery&rsquo;s initial production. Whisky from these casks will not go on general sale.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Members will also receive two miniatures each year so they can taste the spirit as it develops.&nbsp;<a href=\"/shop/product/founders-club-uk-delivery/\">Memberships cost &pound;595</a>.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span><a href=\"http://www.newsandstar.co.uk/news/business/work-underway-on-stills-for-lakes-distillery-1.1105098\">http://www.newsandstar.co.uk/news/business/work-underway-on-stills-for-lakes-distillery-1.1105098</a></span></p>',131),(7,7,'en','RAISING A GLASS TO NEW TIPPLE - 4TH DECEMBER - NORTH WEST EVENING MAIL','raising-glass','blog/North_West_Evening_Mail_3.jpg','Wednesday, 4th December 2013','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">THE first-ever English blended premium whisky, made at a distillery near Bassenthwaite, was been launched in Cockermouth on the eve of the festival.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">IN THE MIX: Paul Currie, managing director of the Lakes Distillery Company at the launch of&nbsp;<a href=\"http://ld.lidemo.co.uk/shop/product/the-one-70cl-in-cylinder/\">The ONE</a></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">THE first-ever English blended premium whisky, made at a distillery near Bassenthwaite, was been launched in Cockermouth on the eve of the festival.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The Lakes Distillery, based in a converted Victorian farm in Setmurthy, revealed its first product,&nbsp;<a href=\"http://ld.lidemo.co.uk/shop/product/the-one-70cl-in-cylinder/\">The ONE</a>.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Dignitaries, business owners and whisky society members were invited to the unveiling of the 40 per cent whisky, at the Trout Hotel.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Paul Currie, managing director, said: &ldquo;We wanted to create a really interesting high-quality whisky. It&rsquo;s something for Cumbria to be proud of.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&ldquo;Being a new Cumbrian company it&rsquo;s great to be launching at Taste Cumbria.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The company will export the whisky to countries in Europe and Asia.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Mr Currie led a whisky masterclass during the festival and the company had a stall selling&nbsp;<a href=\"http://ld.lidemo.co.uk/shop/product/the-one-70cl-in-cylinder/\">The ONE</a>.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The Lakes Distillery is Cumbria&rsquo;s first whisky distillery for over 100 years. It will start producing malt whisky and gin next spring and also plans to open a visitors&rsquo; centre.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/barrow/2.5902/raising-a-glass-to-new-tipple-1.1102580\">http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/barrow/2.5902/raising-a-glass-to-new-tipple-1.1102580</a></p>',131),(8,8,'en','ONE TO WATCH - 25TH NOVEMBER 2013 - LUXE MAGAZINE','one-watch-25th-november-2013-luxe-magazine','blog/Luxe_Magazine.jpg','Monday, 25th November 2013','<p><a href=\"http://issuu.com/room501/docs/luxe_nov-dec13?e=8834296/5676487\">http://issuu.com/room501/docs/luxe_nov-dec13?e=8834296/5676487</a></p>',131),(9,9,'en','REVIEW: THE ONE  BRITISH BLENDED WHISKY - SOMERSET WHISKY BLOG','review-one-','','Today Im reviewing The One, a British Blended Whisky from The Lakes Distillery, a new distillery about to take shape in Cumbria. Official blurb reads as such: The One is a unique blend of exceptional whiskies from the British Isles, each has its own distinctive characterist','<p><span>Today I&rsquo;m reviewing &ldquo;The One&rdquo;, a British Blended Whisky from The Lakes Distillery, a new distillery about to take shape in Cumbria.</span></p>\r\n<p><span><strong>Official&nbsp;blurb reads as such:</strong>&nbsp;The One is a unique blend of exceptional whiskies from the British Isles, each has its own distinctive characteristics, resulting in a whisky of intriguing complexity.</span></p>\r\n<p><span>There are now distilleries producing whisky across the British Isles, and this has led us to create an entirely new concept in blended whiskies &ndash; a British Isles Blend.<br />To create &lsquo;The One&rsquo;, we have searched far and wide to bring together a range of very special whiskies from the British Isles. These have been blended with great care and passion to create a perfectly balanced whisky.</span></p>\r\n<p><strong>Official Tasting Notes:&nbsp;</strong><span>Slightly smoky, sweet and fruity, nutty, with hints of spice.</span></p>\r\n<p><strong>Now on to my review&hellip;</strong></p>\r\n<p><span>The One &ndash; British Blended Whisky / The Lakes Distillery &ndash; 40%</span></p>\r\n<p><span><strong>Colour:</strong>&nbsp;An honest looking light gold.</span></p>\r\n<p><span><strong>Nose:</strong>&nbsp;Malty, cream and vanilla toffee, hints of smoke and hints of north eastern costal promise. Fairly complex, goes one way and then another. Some autumn spiced apples.</span></p>\r\n<p><span><strong>Palate:</strong>&nbsp;The palate isn&rsquo;t too far away from the nose, it&rsquo;s fairly thick, just like the cream and toffee notes lead you to hope. It&rsquo;s nicely sweet and well balanced, it&rsquo;s great to hold on your tongue for a while and to enjoy rolling around. Rather like a Werther&rsquo;s Original caramel sweet.</span></p>\r\n<p><span><strong>Finish:</strong>&nbsp;Warming and oily, thickly creamy with vanilla notes and smoky hints lasting out, fruits and wood lasting even longer still.</span></p>\r\n<p><span><strong>Thoughts:</strong>&nbsp;A really quality blend this, crafted with obvious love. If the output of the yet-to-be-built distillery is crafted with the love this that has then I rather think we have exciting times ahead for another English born whisky (producers of which are still countable on one hand). It&rsquo;s a slight shame that this is assumedly chill-filtered, it would really be quite something if it weren&rsquo;t and was presented at 46% ABV. Maybe for another release in the future?</span></p>\r\n<p><strong>Score: 87</strong></p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.somersetwhisky.com/index.php/review-the-one-british-blended-whisky/\">http://www.somersetwhisky.com/index.php/review-the-one-british-blended-whisky/</a></p>',178),(10,10,'en','The Lakes distillery is a very exciting new whisky distillery that is in the processes of building in one of the nicest places on earth (in the UK, that is, ok?), and it is going to be the first distillery built there for the last 100 years or so. I reall','lakes-distillery-','','The Lakes distillery is a very exciting new whisky distillery that is in the processes of building in one of the nicest places on earth (in the UK, that is, ok?), and it is going to be the first distillery built there for the last 100 years or so. I really wanted to visit the distillery location','<p><span><span>The Lakes distillery is a very exciting new whisky distillery that is in the processes of building in one of the nicest places on earth (in the UK, that is, ok?), and it is going to be the first distillery built there for the last 100 years or so. I really wanted to visit the distillery location last August when I was in the Lakes District with the family, but schedule issues with both me and Paul who was very nice and inviting, made it quite impossible at the time.&nbsp; Anyways, the distillery is not running yet but is scheduled to start distilling this spring (2014), It shall first release a Gin, and open its gates for visitors in the visitor centre, as well as a shop, a restaurant and bar. Sounds like a wonderful place to visit next time you&rsquo;re there.</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span><span>They have not really distilled anything yet, but have created their first prodcut already, in the form of a Blended whisky, A British whisky that is. What does that really mean? Essentially that the whiskies used are all distilled in the British Isles , not sure what really goes into that but there are some hints you can use to figure that out if you&rsquo;re really into that&hellip;</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span><span>The bottle looks lovely too, but let&rsquo;s see what&rsquo;s inside&hellip;</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span><span><a href=\"/shop\">The One Blended whisky, 40% , &pound;29.95</a></span></span></p>',131),(11,11,'en','THE ONE','the-one','blog/Living_Room_Whisky_1.jpg','Wednesday, 6th November 2013','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">We&rsquo;re particularly excited about the plans for the first distillery to be built in the Lake District for over 100 years. So excited in fact that we couldn&rsquo;t even wait for it to be built and have already visited the site and had a chat with the lovely managing director Paul Currie.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A lot has happened since we last visited the distillery; and that includes the launch of a brand new blended whisky that we&rsquo;ll discuss shortly. Renovation work is starting this month with production scheduled to begin in Spring 2014. Following this the Lakes Gin will be released and the distillery will accept visitors to its visitor centre, shop, bistro and bar from the summer. All in all its exciting times up at Bassenthwaite and we&rsquo;re looking forward to getting back up there to check on progress!</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">The One</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">With production not beginning until next year we were surprised to see a whisky being launched by the Lakes Distillery in Autumn 2013. It was however a lovely surprise, unlike the horror of opening a Christmas gift to discover that yet again your clever relative managed to stuff some socks into a particularly rare and sadly empty malt bottle. This whisky is a blend created from whiskies from around the British Isles. There is no information as to the constituent parts but we could take some educated guesses on some components based upon their geography! It would be remiss not to mention the bottle itself &ndash; the design is simple and gorgeous and based on looks alone would grace any decent whisky shelf. However, what we&rsquo;re really interested in is the spirit. The One is a blended whisky, bottled at 40% and here is what we thought.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The&nbsp;nose&nbsp;begins with a lovely&nbsp;creamy sweet vanilla&nbsp;fudge&nbsp;note. We&rsquo;re then off on a journey around the Isles as we&rsquo;re treated to a floral bouquet&nbsp;with top notes of&nbsp;heather&nbsp;and&nbsp;honey.&nbsp;White grapes come through strongly only to be tempered by&nbsp;icing sugar&nbsp;and rather interestingly &ndash; some&nbsp;cumin seeds!</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The&nbsp;palate&nbsp;is light and&nbsp;vibrant&nbsp;with an almost&nbsp;hoppy&nbsp;like taste. There is a lot of&nbsp;spice&nbsp;and&nbsp;salt&nbsp;on the tip of the tongue, with some cayenne&nbsp;further back in the mouth.&nbsp;Grapes&nbsp;and&nbsp;coriander leaves&nbsp;are briefly present before a&nbsp;golden syrup&nbsp;and&nbsp;custard&nbsp;like sweetness takes over and fills the mouth. The whisky finishes with a flourish; lots of lingering spice and heat with an abundance of&nbsp;white chocolate chips.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The One is a good solid blend and well worth considering as we move into the winter months. Now, obviously it hasn&rsquo;t been distilled by the Lakes Distillery but if this is the care and attention they&rsquo;re putting in to their products, and having seen the care and attention that&rsquo;s going into their site, we&rsquo;re now even more excited about the first spirits to run off their stills! 2014 will be an exciting time for a remote corner of Cumbria, so get involved early and enjoy the first release from a distillery that we hope will be doing fabulous things for English whisky in 2014 and beyond.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://www.livingroomwhisky.com/project/the-one-the-lakes-distillery/\">Living Room Whisky</a></p>',131),(12,12,'en','MINE\'S AN ENGLISH ','mines-english','blog/The_Economist.jpg','Saturday, 12th October 2013','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">WITH its lofty peaks, peaty water and the steady drip of rain on heather, Bassenthwaite seems an ideal place to make whisky. The nearest Scotch distillery is just 60 miles away. But when the Lakes Distillery, which has just been given planning permission, bottles its first casks of single malt in a few years&rsquo; time, strict EU rules will make it something quite different. It might look like Scotch and taste like Scotch, but the dram will be English.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&ldquo;It was a stroke of genius coining &lsquo;Scotch&rsquo; for a drink that can be made successfully anywhere,&rdquo; says Andrew Nelstrop, a Norfolk farmer who in 2006 opened England&rsquo;s first new distillery for more than a century. With the help of a former Laphroaig distiller&mdash;a contribution more crucial than any amount of peat or rainfall&mdash;St George&rsquo;s Distillery now sells its English Whisky Company single malts to supermarkets in England, distributors overseas, and even in Scotland. In December Adnams, a Suffolk brewer, will bottle whisky that has been sitting in casks for three years&mdash;the time it takes for the European Union to recognise fermented cereal mash as whisky. The London Distillery Company in Battersea is soon to start barrelling a single malt aimed at young urbanites.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">When that happens, England will have roughly the same number of whisky distilleries as it did in the 19th century. The reasons they closed are murky: a scarcity of equipment as Scottish whisky took off probably played a part. But the resurgence of English whisky is no mystery. Global demand is surging. In emerging economies it is the high-status tipple for a burgeoning middle class. Growth is strong even in mature markets like America. Over the last decade exports of Scotch have risen by 87%, reaching &pound;4.3 billion ($7 billion) in 2012.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Progress on free trade could drive sales much higher. In India, which drinks almost as much whisky as the rest of the world put together, tariffs of 150% have long put imported whisky beyond most drinkers&rsquo; reach. But with the EU hoping to win a tariff reduction under a free-trade agreement with the subcontinent, imbibers of cheap domestic brands such as Bagpiper and Antiquity may soon be able to enjoy whiskies made in, or close to, Scotland.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://www.economist.com/news/britain/21587838-mines-english\">The Economist</a></p>',131),(13,13,'en','THE LAKES DISTILLERY LAUNCH IT\'S FIRST WHISKY','lakes-distillery','blog/Todo_Whisky.jpg','Friday, 4th October 2013','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Do you remember&nbsp;The Lakes Distillery?</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">On May 21 we told as&nbsp;Paul Currie&nbsp;, co-founder of Isle of Arran, was to open a<span style=\"color: #000000;\">&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #000000;\">new distillery in the Lake District</span>&nbsp;&nbsp;in&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #000000;\">Cumbria</span>&nbsp;</span>, northwest England.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Now, sooner than they had anticipated, The Lakes Distillery has announced their first&nbsp;blend&nbsp;, called \"&nbsp;The One&nbsp;\", the first whiskey created in that area&nbsp;for over 100 years&nbsp;.&nbsp;According to the distiller, The One has merged with walnut smoked sweet and fruity flavors, with notes of spice.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The new blend will be available in the&nbsp;online store of the distillery&nbsp;(have not yet built a visitor center) or at various retail stores in Britain.&nbsp;In addition, the distillery claims to already have the support of various European and Asian distributors, so maybe The One can get to Spain.&nbsp;Its suggested retail price is about&nbsp;35 euros.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">As we advance, The Lakes Distillery has created a&nbsp;<a href=\"/members/founders-club\">Founders Club</a>&nbsp;, which gives the opportunity to purchase one of the first 100 barrels of this new distillery.&nbsp;Thus, from 2015 each year for a total of 10 members of the club will receive a 70cl bottle of whiskey that is already getting old.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Finally The Lakes Distillery has also dated the release of their&nbsp;single malt&nbsp;called&nbsp;<a href=\"/brands/the-lakes-malt\">The Lakes Malt</a>&nbsp;, to be launched in 2019.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://todowhisky.es/2013/10/the-lakes-distillery-lanza-su-primer-whisky/\">Todo Whisky Blogger</a></p>',131),(14,14,'en','LAKES DISTILLERY PRODUCE FIRST BRITISH BLENDED WHISKY ','lakes-distillery-produces-first-british-blended','blog/Harpers.jpg','Monday, 7th October 2013','<p><a href=\"http://www.harpers.co.uk/news/lakes-distillery-to-produce-first-british-blended-whisky/350218.article\">http://www.harpers.co.uk/news/lakes-distillery-to-produce-first-british-blended-whisky/350218.article</a></p>',131),(15,15,'en','FIRST EVER BRITISH BLENDED WHISKY RELEASED','first-ever-british-whisky-released','blog/The_Spirits_Business_1.jpg','Wednesday, 2nd October 2013','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A&nbsp;UK distillery has created the first British blended whisky, bringing together a range of whiskies from the British Isles.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">While the Scotch market is brimming with blended malts, The One is the first British blended whisky</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The Lakes Distillery, Cumbria&rsquo;s first whisky distillery for over 100 years, has launched The One British blended whisky, an expression described as &ldquo;slightly smoky, sweet and fruity, nutty, with hints of spice&rdquo;.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The One will be sold in The Lakes Distillery online shop as well as a small number of outlets in the UK.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The distillery has also announced that it will be looking to develop the brand in export markets and is in discussions with partners in a number of markets in Europe and Asia.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Paul Currie, managing director of The Lakes Distillery, said: &ldquo;We have kept the bottle, branding and even the name of The One tightly under wraps so we were incredibly proud to launch it at last.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&ldquo;The One and The Lakes Distillery are very strong Cumbrian brands and we hope to build on this in both national and international markets so that both become synonymous with Cumbria.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In addition to this launch, The Lakes Distillery will be looking to start distilling its own Cumbrian malt whisky and gin next spring.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The spirits producer has recently created a &lsquo;Founders&rsquo; Club&rsquo;, where members will receive a bottle of maturing whisky from the first 100 casks of Lakes Malt every year for 10 years from 2015.</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.thespiritsbusiness.com/2013/10/first-ever-british-blended-whisky-released/\">The Spirits Business</a></p>',131),(16,16,'en','THE LAKES DISTILLERY LAUNCHES THE FIRST BRITISH BLENDED WHISKY ','lakes-distillery-launches-the-first-britsh-blended','blog/Cumbria_24_2.jpg','Monday, 30th September 2013','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The Lakes Distillery, Cumbria&rsquo;s first whisky distillery for over 100 years, launched its inaugural product last week; A British Isles blend named &lsquo;The One&rsquo;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Over 50 guests came together to celebrate the launch in a marquee on the grounds of Cockermouth&rsquo;s Trout Hotel.&nbsp; The unique, contemporary bottle and branding of The One was unveiled by Paul Currie, Managing Director of The Lakes Distillery, before guests were treated to a tasting of the blend, followed by a lunch of Cumbrian tapas and a tour of the distillery site near Bassenthwaite.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The One, the very first British blended whisky, brings together a range of exceptional whiskies from around the British Isles.&nbsp; Each has its own distinctive characteristics, melded with great care and passion to create a perfectly balanced whisky of intriguing complexity; slightly smoky, sweet and fruity, nutty, with hints of spice.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Paul Currie said:<br />&ldquo;We have kept the bottle, branding and even the name of The One tightly under wraps so we were incredibly proud to officially launch it at last. The One and The Lakes Distillery are very strong Cumbrian brands and we hope to build on this in both national and international markets so that both become synonymous with Cumbria.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&ldquo;The next step for us now is the development of our site at Setmurthy and preparing to start production of The Lakes Malt and The Lakes Gin in Spring next year. This is a very exciting time.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The Lakes Distillery is idyllically housed in a former Victorian model farm in a spectacular secluded setting.&nbsp; By next summer the characterful site will also include a visitor centre offering supervised distillery tours, a bistro, bar and shop, creating over 30 jobs and making it a key Lake District attraction.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://www.cumbria24.com/lake-district/2013/09/30/lakes-distillery-launches-first-british-blended-whisky?quicktabs_news_feeds=0\">Cumbria 24</a></p>',131),(18,18,'en','ENGLISH DISTILLERY PRODUCES THE VERY FIRST BRITISH BLENDED WHISKY ','english-distillery-produces-first-british-blend','blog/SYS_Media.jpg','Monday, 30th September 2013','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The Lakes Distillery, Cumbria\'s first whisky distillery for over 100 years, has created an entirely new concept in blended whiskies for its inaugural product: A British Isles blend.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">There is a host of Scotch blends on the market, but \'The One\', the very first British blended whisky, brings together a range of exceptional whiskies from around the British Isles. Each has its own distinctive characteristics, melded with great care and passion to create a perfectly balanced whisky of intriguing complexity; slightly smoky, sweet and fruity, nutty, with hints of spice.<br /><br />The One will be sold in The Lakes Distillery\'s online shop and in a small number of carefully chosen outlets in the UK. The distillery will place a great emphasis on developing the brand in export markets and is already in discussions with partners in a number of markets in Europe and Asia.<br /><br />The Lakes Distillery, idyllically housed in a secluded former Victorian model farm in the Lake District, will make the most of Cumbria\'s perfect whisky producing conditions and will start distilling its own Cumbrian malt whisky and gin in Spring next year. The characterful site will also include a visitor centre offering supervised distillery tours, a bistro, bar and shop.<br /><br />As well as launching The One, the innovative distillery has created a unique Founders\'\' Club, providing a one-off chance to obtain whisky from its first 100 casks of Lakes Malt. Each year for ten years from 2015, members will receive a 70cl bottle of the maturing whisky, each with a limited edition label, forming a rare collection of The Lakes Distillery\'s first ever production.<br /><br />Founders\' Club members will be provided with two miniatures each year allowing them to taste the spirit as it develops into a wonderful single malt whisky. Delivery of the first bottle will be in 2015 and these casks are exclusively for Founders\' Club members.<br /><br />Overseen by Paul Currie, co-founder of the award-winning Arran Distillery and Alan Rutherford, former Production Director at Diageo, The Lakes Distillery\'s tremendous whisky expertise has led to the successful creation of The One and the future Lakes Malt.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://www.sys-con.com/node/2814985\">SYS Media</a></p>',131),(20,20,'en','WEST CUMBRIAN WHISKY IS LAUNCHED','west-cumbrian-whisky-is-launched','blog/Times__Star_2.jpg','Friday, 27th September 2013','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The first ever British blended premium whisky, made at a distillery near Bassenthwaite, was launched in Cockermouth yesterday.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The Lakes Distillery, based at a converted Victorian farm in Setmurthy, revealed its first product, The One, at the Trout Hotel on the eve of the Taste Cumbria Food Festival.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Dignitaries, business owners and whisky society members were invited to the unveiling of the 40 per cent proof whisky.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Paul Currie, managing director, said: &ldquo;We wanted to create a really interesting high quality whisky. It&rsquo;s something for Cumbria to be proud of.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&ldquo;Being a new Cumbrian company, it&rsquo;s great to be launching at Taste Cumbria.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">He said that the company will export its whisky to countries in Europe and Asia.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Mr Currie will lead a whisky masterclass during the food festival and the company will have a stall selling The One.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">John Simmons, 67, of Southwaite, near Cockermouth, who is honorary president of the Crusty Bones whisky society based in Cockermouth, said: &ldquo;It&rsquo;s excellent. I was really surprised to find out it was a blended whisky rather than a single malt.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Julie Watson, owner of Cockermouth Sweet Shop on Main Street, said: &ldquo;It&rsquo;s an amazing whisky and I am sure it will do really well.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Kate Parry, general manager at Cockermouth&rsquo;s Kirkgate Centre, said: &ldquo;I think it&rsquo;s beautiful. I am really proud that it&rsquo;s going to be produced so close to Cockermouth. It&rsquo;s a really great achievement.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The Lakes Distillery is Cumbria&rsquo;s first whisky distillery for over 100 years.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">It will start producing malt whisky and gin next spring and plans to open a visitors&rsquo; centre.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://www.timesandstar.co.uk/news/other/west-cumbrian-whisky-is-launched-1.1087529\">The Times &amp; Star</a></p>',131),(21,21,'en','FIRST WHISKY FROM NEW LAKES DISTILLERY ','first-whisky-from-new-lakes-distillery','blog/North_West_Evening_Mail_2.jpg','Friday, 20th September 2013','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The Lakes Distillery launches its first whisky next week as part of the Taste Cumbria food festival in Cockermouth.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A consortium of private investors led by Paul Currie, a co-founder of the Isle of Arran Distillery, is converting a Victorian farm at Setmurthy, near Bassenthwaite, into a &pound;2.5m distillery.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Building work should start next month and it aims to produce malt whisky and gin from next spring.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A visitor centre with bar, bistro and shop will follow later in the year. Production is expected to reach 300,000 bottles a year &ndash; although the distillery will have the capacity to produce a million bottles &ndash; and the site should support 27 jobs.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The first product to be released under the Lakes Distillery brand is a blend of grain and malt whiskies from other British distilleries. It is described as &ldquo;a unique blend of exceptional whiskies&rdquo; that together create &ldquo;a whisky of intriguing complexity&rdquo;.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The name and packaging are being kept under wraps until the launch at Cockermouth&rsquo;s Trout Hotel next Thursday.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Mr Currie, managing director of the business, said: &ldquo;The Lakes Distillery is an intrinsically Cumbrian brand and we are immensely proud of our Cumbrian home.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&ldquo;Our whiskies will, after all, be a product of our remarkable landscape, so it seemed only fitting that we chose Cumbria&rsquo;s leading food festival as the place to launch our first creation.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">He will lead a whisky masterclass next Saturday, as part of Taste Cumbria, providing tastings, an insight into the world of whisky and an opportunity to sample the new blend.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Meanwhile, the Lakes Distillery has launched a founders&rsquo; club for enthusiasts. Members receive one 70cl bottle each year for the first 10 years, starting in 2015, drawn from the distillery&rsquo;s initial production.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Whisky from these casks will not be on sale to the general public. They also receive two miniatures each year so they can taste the spirit as it develops. Memberships costs &pound;595.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The Lakes Distillery aims to build on the huge commercial success of Scottish malt whisky &ndash; exports were worth &pound;4.27bn last year, representing a quarter of Britain&rsquo;s food and drink exports.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://www.nwemail.co.uk/first-whisky-from-new-lakes-distillery-1.1086010\">North West Evening Mail</a></p>',131),(22,22,'en','NEW WHISKY SET TO BE CREATED AT A BASSENTHWAITE DISTILLERY','new-whisky-set-to-be-created-at-bassenthwaite-dist','blog/The_Journal_1.jpg','Thursday, 19th September 2013','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The Lakes Distillery, at Bassenthwaite, which has just won planning permission, is a &pound;2.5m venture by a consortium of investors headed by Nigel Mills and Paul Currie.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A news whisky is being created at a distillery about to be built in the heart of the Lake District.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The Lakes Distillery, at Bassenthwaite, which has just won planning permission, is a &pound;2.5m venture by a consortium of investors headed by Nigel Mills and Paul Currie and anticipated to employ 27 people.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Mills founded the Whitley Bay-based Mills Group before selling the business to Tesco for more than &pound;20m in 2011, while Currie is co-founder of award-winning Isle of Arran distillery in Scotland.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The pair aim to produce the equivalent of 300,000 bottles of single malt whisky per year at the distillery, housed in a converted model farm on the edge of picturesque Bassenthwaite near Keswick.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Building work will begin next month and is due to be completed in 2014.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Mills said: &ldquo;We&rsquo;ve put a board together comprising myself, Paul, my former finance director at Mills Group, Martin Stokoe, and Gary Thornton.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&ldquo;We&rsquo;ve managing to raise between &pound;1m and &pound;2m and we&rsquo;ve also received some European grant funding to get the business started.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Currie added: &ldquo;We are embarking on an exciting new venture to create a world-class, single malt whisky at the heart of the Lake District.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&ldquo;As co-founder of the award-winning Arran Distillery in Scotland, I have more than 20 years&rsquo; experience of the whisky industry. However, this new project, which will see whisky produced in the Lake District for the first time in 200 years, has really fired my imagination - not least because the area we have chosen possesses the finest natural ingredients.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The water the distillery is planned to use has its source at Sprinkling Tarn and is of unparalleled purity, Currie said, while the mountain air and the peaty foothills of iconic Scafell Pike will combine to create a lightly peated malt.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The site will also house a visitor centre with a bar, bistro and shop, each aimed at showcasing locally-sourced Cumbrian produce with regular tours for visitors, and development will be undertaken using environmentally-friendly and sustainable materials,</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Mills said: &ldquo;There is only one other whisky distillery in England and that&rsquo;s in Norfolk but it is very much a smaller operation to what we are trying to do in the Lake District.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The Lakes Distillery team is comprised of a consortium of experienced investors and some of the whisky industry&rsquo;s leading authorities, with Alan Rutherford, former production director at Diageo and Council Member of the Scotch Whisky Association, overseeing the operation.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The distilling plant uses the industry&rsquo;s latest technology while the copper stills will be made to a unique design and a range of different casks will be used to ensure that the spirit is perfectly matured.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://www.thejournal.co.uk/business/business-news/new-whisky-set-created-bassenthwaite-6062241\">The Journal</a></p>',131),(23,23,'en','FIRST PRODUCT FROM THE LAKES DISTILLERY TO BE LAUNCHED AT TASTE CUMBRIA ','first-product-from-lakes-distillery-launched','blog/Cumbria_24_1.jpg','Monday, 2nd September 2013','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>The Lakes Distillery will launch its very first product &ndash; a unique premium blended whisky - at the Taste Cumbria food festival in Cockermouth this September.</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The blended whisky, which will be available to buy at The Lakes Distillery&rsquo;s festival stand, will be the first ever&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/brands/brand-x\">British blend</a>&nbsp;&ndash; carefully crafted with grain and malt whiskies from across the British Isles. Each element has its own distinctive characteristics and these have been melded with great care and passion to create a whisky of intriguing complexity.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The brand name of the product and its innovative packaging, will be kept firmly under wraps until Taste Cumbria.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Founder and Managing Director of The Lakes Distillery, Paul Currie, will lead a whisky master-class during the festival too, providing tastings, an insight into the world of whisky and its creation around the globe and even the opportunity to sample the brand&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/brands/brand-x\">new blended whisky.</a></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Paul said:&nbsp;&ldquo;The Lakes Distillery is an intrinsically Cumbrian brand, we are immensely proud of our Cumbrian home - our whiskies will, after all, be a product of our remarkable landscape, so it seemed only fitting that we chose Cumbria&rsquo;s leading food festival as the place to launch our first creation.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&ldquo;All will be revealed at Taste Cumbria, but it&rsquo;s safe to say that our first product is incredibly exciting and will be very special.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The Lakes Distillery is Cumbria&rsquo;s first whisky distillery for over 100 years and is located between Cockermouth and Keswick, idyllically housed in a former<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/our-distillery/our-buildings\">Victorian model farm</a>, next to the River Derwent.&nbsp; It will start producing&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/brands/the-lakes-malt\">malt whisky</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/brands/the-lakes-gin\">gin</a>&nbsp;in Spring next year and in Summer 2014 will open its visitor centre complete with&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/distillery-bar-and-bistro\">bar and bistro</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/shop\">shop</a>, making it a key attraction for visitors to the county, creating jobs and helping to continue raising the profile of the Western Lake District as an outstanding place to visit.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Membership for The Lakes Distillery&rsquo;s&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/members/founders-club\">Founders&rsquo; Club</a>&nbsp;is currently open, providing a one-off chance to obtain whisky from the first 100 casks of its Lakes Malt, but is fast being taken up as its such a rare opportunity to own a piece of whisky history from a distillery whose team is a veritable who&rsquo;s who of the whisky world&hellip;Paul Currie himself co-founded the award-winning Aaran Distillery and the production will be overseen by one of Scotland&rsquo;s foremost whisky experts, Alan Rutherford, former Production Director at Diageo.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Taste Cumbria takes place in Cockermouth on the 28th and 29th of September and The Lakes Distillery&rsquo;s&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/brands/brand-x\">new blended whisky</a>&nbsp;will be available to buy throughout.&nbsp; Paul&rsquo;s master-class is at 3pm on the Saturday and tickets cost &pound;5 per person.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://www.cumbria24.com/lake-district/2013/09/02/first-product-lakes-distillery-be-launched-taste-cumbria\">By Cumbria 24</a></p>',131),(24,24,'en','AMAZING BARROW MADE CAKE IS JUST THE TONIC FOR CUMBRIA DISTILLERYS LAUNCH','amazing-barrow-made-cake','blog/North_West_Evening_Mail_1.jpg','Wednesday, 28th August 2013','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>A BAKER was given the honour of creating a spectacular cake crafted as a scale model of a pioneering new Lakes business.</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Elliot Johnson&rsquo;s superb cake was a star attraction as more than 100 guests celebrated the launch of the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/members/founders-club\">Founders&rsquo; Club&nbsp;</a>for The Lakes Distillery &ndash; Cumbria&rsquo;s first whisky distillery for more than 100 years.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The launch event, held in a marquee in the grounds of the Trout Hotel in Cockermouth, was hosted by Paul Currie, the distillery&rsquo;s managing director and Gavin D Smith, one of the world&rsquo;s leading whisky writers, who together presented a tasting of five whiskies from around the globe.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The event marked the start of a schedule of opening activity for the brand new distillery, which is set to start producing&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/brands/the-lakes-malt\">malt whisky</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/brands/the-lakes-gin\">gin</a>&nbsp;in spring next year.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The spectacular cake, crafted in the design of The Lakes Distillery site, was created by Mr Johnson of Lakes Bakery, Dalton Road, Barrow, and was donated to the nearby St Oswald&rsquo;s Hospice following Sunday&rsquo;s event.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Mr Johnson was approached by the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/members/founders-club\">Founders&rsquo; Club</a>&nbsp;and asked to create the cake after they heard his Bridge House cake won the Lakeland Cake of the Year award in the annual contest at Briery Wood Hotel, Windermere, earlier this year.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Mr Johnson said &ldquo;It was such an honour to be able to use my skills to help mark such an event.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&ldquo;From a business point of view it&rsquo;s also wonderful to be able to publicise my cakes and Lakes Bakery&rsquo;s name.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&ldquo;The cake turned out better than I expected and I was extremely pleased with the end product.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/amazing-barrow-made-cake-is-just-the-tonic-for-cumbria-distillery-s-launch-1.1080860\">North West Evening Mail</a></p>',131),(25,25,'en','TIPPLES DOWNED AT DISTILLERY LAUNCH ','tipples-downed-distillery-launch','blog/Times__Star_1.jpg','Friday, 23rd August 2013','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>More than 100 guests came together to celebrate the Cumbrian launch of the Founders&rsquo; Club for The Lakes Distillery &ndash; Cumbria&rsquo;s first whisky distillery for over 100 years.</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Paul Currie is converting the Victorian Low Barkhouse Farm at Setmurthy, near Cockermouth, into a &pound;1.5 million distillery. The launch event was held in a marquee in the grounds of the Trout Hotel, Cockermouth. It was hosted by Mr Currie and Gavin D Smith, one of the world&rsquo;s leading whisky writers, who together presented a tasting of five whiskies from around the globe.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The event marked the start of a schedule of activity for the distillery, which is set to start producing<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/brands/the-lakes-malt\">malt whisky&nbsp;</a>and&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/brands/the-lakes-gin\">gin</a>&nbsp;next spring.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The Lakes Distillery, next to the River Derwent, will also have a visitor&rsquo;s centre, due to open next summer, with a&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/distillery-bar-and-bistro\">bar, bistro</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/shop\">shop</a>.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/members/founders-club\">Founders\' club</a>&nbsp;is the first phase of the distillery&rsquo;s opening and provides a one-off chance to obtain whisky from the inaugural 100 casks of its Lakes Malt. Each year for 10 years from 2015, members will receive a 70cl bottle of the maturing whisky. The first 100 casks will not be available to the general public and are exclusively for&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/members/founders-club\">Founders&rsquo; Club</a>&nbsp;members.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Mr Currie said: &ldquo;We created the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/members/founders-club\">Founders&rsquo; Club</a>&nbsp;as we wanted local people to join us on our journey to becoming a renowned premium whisky producer.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&ldquo;We have been overwhelmed with the interest we have received and even prior to our launch event on Sunday we had people signing up to be members.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">It is expected that the distillery will produce 100,000 litres of whisky a year plus gin.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">It will contain two stills for the production of whisky. They will have a capacity of 3,500 litres and are being built in Scotland.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Mr Currie said there would be a third small still to produce a Lakeland gin using local juniper berries.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Mr Currie co-founded the award-winning Arran Distillery and the production at the Lakes Distillery will be overseen by one of Scotland&rsquo;s foremost whisky experts, Alan Rutherford, former production director at Diageo.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Published by&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.timesandstar.co.uk/\">http://www.timesandstar.co.uk</a></p>',131),(26,26,'en','LAKES DISTILLERY LAUNCHES UNIQUE CHANCE TO OWN A PART OF CUMBRIAN HISTORY ','lakes-distillery-launches-unique-chance','blog/Cumbria_24.jpg','Wednesday, 21st August','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Over 100 guests came together on Sunday (18th August) to celebrate the Cumbrian launch of the Founders&rsquo; Club for The Lakes Distillery &ndash; Cumbria&rsquo;s first whisky distillery for over 100 years.</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The launch event, held in a marquee in the grounds of the Trout Hotel in Cockermouth, was hosted by Paul Currie, the Distillery&rsquo;s Managing Director and Gavin D. Smith, one of the world&rsquo;s leading whisky writers, who together presented a tasting of five whiskies from around the globe.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The event marked the start of a schedule of opening activity for the brand new Distillery, which is set to start producing&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/brands/the-lakes-malt\">malt whisky</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/brands/the-lakes-gin\">gin</a>&nbsp;in Spring next year.&nbsp; The Lakes Distillery, which will be idyllically housed in historic&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/our-distillery/our-buildings\">buildings</a>&nbsp;next to the River Derwent, will also boast a Visitor Centre, due to open in Summer 2014, complete with bar and bistro and shop, making it a key attraction for visitors to the county.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/members/founders-club\">Founders&rsquo; Club</a>&nbsp;is the first phase of the Distillery&rsquo;s opening and provides a one-off chance to obtain whisky from the inaugural 100 casks of its Lakes Malt.&nbsp; Each year for ten years from 2015, members will receive a 70cl bottle of the maturing whisky, each with unique limited edition labels, forming a rare collection of The Lakes Distillery&rsquo;s first ever production. The first 100 casks will not be available to the general public and are exclusively for&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/members/founders-club\">Founders&rsquo; Club</a>&nbsp;members.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Paul Currie said:<br />&ldquo;We created the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/members/founders-club\">Founders&rsquo; Club</a>&nbsp;as we wanted local people to join us on our journey to becoming a renowned premium whisky producer.&nbsp; We have been overwhelmed with the interest we have received, even prior to our launch event on Sunday we had people signing up to be members.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&ldquo;This is an incredibly exciting time for us and for the Western Lake District too; The Lakes Distillery will create outstanding products that are Cumbrian through and through.&nbsp; We aim to become an intrinsic part of the Western Lake District experience, helping to support the local economy and further enhance Cumbria&rsquo;s reputation for excellent quality.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/members/founders-club\">Founders&rsquo; Club</a>&nbsp;provides an exceptional opportunity to own a piece of whisky history from a distillery whose team is a veritable who&rsquo;s who of the whisky world&hellip;Paul Currie himself co-founded the award-winning Aaran Distillery and the production will be overseen by one of Scotland&rsquo;s foremost whisky experts, Alan Rutherford, former Production Director at Diageo.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A spectacular cake crafted in the design of The Lakes Distillery site was donated to St. Oswald&rsquo;s Hospice following Sunday&rsquo;s event.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Reported by Maurice Chesworth&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://www.cumbria24.com/news/2013/08/21/lakes-distillery-launches-unique-chance-own-part-cumbrian-history\">By Cumbria 24</a></p>',131),(29,29,'en','2.5M BASSENTHWAITE LAKE DISTILLERY PROJECT BRINGS JOBS BOOST ','lake-district-project-brings-jobs-boost','blog/The_Journal.jpg','Wednesday, 19th June 2013','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>LAW firm Watson Burton has advised The Lakes Distillery Company on the creation of Cumbria&rsquo;s first whisky distillery in over 100 years in a &pound;2.5m venture.</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The distillery is set to open its doors on the edge of picturesque Bassenthwaite Lake, reviving an age-old tradition as well as providing a boost to the local economy.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Founded by a consortium of private investors, The Lakes Distillery will be headed by Paul Currie, co-founder of award-winning Isle of Arran distillery in Scotland.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Aiming to produce the equivalent of 300,000 bottles of&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/brands/the-lakes-malt\">single malt whisky&nbsp;</a>per year with the capacity to produce 1,000,000, the distillery will be housed in a converted model farm and will create 27 jobs in the region.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The distilling plant will use the industry&rsquo;s latest technology while the copper stills will be made to a unique design and a range of different casks will be used to ensure that the spirit is perfectly matured.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Watson Burton, which has offices in Newcastle and London advised The Lakes Distillery Company in co-ordinating the investments.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The corporate team&rsquo;s associate Paul Wigham and solicitor Helen Foy drafted and negotiated the agreements with the consortium of investors and advised on the legal aspects of establishing the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/members/founders-club\">Founders&rsquo; Club,</a>&nbsp;which offers enthusiasts the opportunity to be among the first in the world to taste and own&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/members/founders-club\">The Lakes Malt</a>.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The site will also house a visitor centre with a&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/distillery-bar-and-bistro\">bar, bistro</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/shop\">shop</a>, each aimed at showcasing locally-sourced Cumbrian produce with regular tours for visitors.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The development of the site, which will be undertaken using environmentally-friendly and sustainable materials, is scheduled to start in the autumn with the stills ordered and due for delivery in the early part of 2014.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Paul Wigham said: &ldquo;Not only will this provide a real boost for the local economy, it will hugely raise the profile of Bassenthwaite Lake as a focal point in England for the whisky industry. We are delighted to have acted as part of the team in helping the investors&rsquo; vision become a reality and are confident that this will be a successful venture for all involved when distilling commences next year.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Lakes Distillery Company chairman Nigel Mills said: &ldquo;This is a once in a lifetime opportunity to make whisky history by building a distillery in the Lake District National Park which will not only create jobs but will also eventually become a key food and beverage destination for the people of Cumbria and one of the North West&rsquo;s leading tourist attractions.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://www.thejournal.co.uk/business/business-news/25m-bassenthwaite-lake-distillery-project-4715069\">By The Journal</a></p>',131),(30,30,'en','WATSON BURTON RAISES DRAM TO NEW DISTILLERY - 17TH JUNE 2013','watson-burton','','Law firm Watson Burton has advised The Lakes Distillery Company on the creation of Cumbria\'s first whisky distillery in more than 100 years. The 2.5m venture, founded by a consortium of private investors, will be headed by Paul Currie and is set to open its doors on the edge of Bassenthwait\r\n','<p><strong>Law firm Watson Burton has advised The Lakes Distillery Company on the creation of Cumbria\'s first whisky distillery in more than 100 years.</strong></p>\r\n<p>The &pound;2.5m venture, founded by a consortium of private investors, will be headed by Paul Currie and is set to open its doors on the edge of Bassenthwaite Lake.</p>\r\n<p>\"We are delighted to be bringing this ancient tradition back to the region and are confident we will be able to produce an outstanding&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/brands/the-lakes-malt\">single malt</a>,\" said Currie. \"It is also our intention that the distillery will become one of the biggest tourist attractions in the Lakes.\"</p>\r\n<p>Aiming to produce the equivalent of 300,000 bottles of&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/brands/the-lakes-malt\">single malt whisky</a>&nbsp;per year with the capacity to produce one million, the distillery will be housed in a converted model farm and will create 27 jobs in the region.</p>\r\n<p>Watson Burton\'s corporate team advised The Lakes Distillery Company in coordinating the investments.</p>\r\n<p>Associate Paul Wigham and solicitor Helen Foy drafted and negotiated the agreements with the consortium of investors and advised on the legal aspects of establishing the Founders\' Club, which offers enthusiasts the opportunity to be among the first in the world to taste and own The Lakes Malt.</p>\r\n<p>\"This distillery has huge appeal for whisky enthusiasts visiting the Lakes,\" said Wigham. \"Not only will this provide a real boost for the local economy, it will hugely raise the profile of Bassenthwaite Lake as a focal point in England for the whisky industry.</p>\r\n<p>\"We are delighted to have acted as part of the team in helping the investors\' vision become a reality and are confident that this will be a successful venture for all involved when distilling commences next year.\"</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.insidermedia.com/insider/north-east/92302-/index.html\">By Insider Media Ltd</a></p>',131),(31,31,'en','LAKES DRAM DREAM TAKES SHAPE','lakes-dram-dream-takes-shape','blog/Cheers.jpg','Tuesday, 4th June 2014','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>A new whisky distillery is set to open in the heart of The Lake District. The Lakes Distillery, the first of its kind in Cumbria in more than 100 years, is planned for the edge of picturesque Bassenthwaite Lake &ndash; and could create a much needed boost to the local economy.</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The &pound;2.5m venture, which has been founded by a consortium of private investors who include Nigel Mills, who sold his North East chain of newsagents to Tesco, and Geoff Hodgson, former chief executive of the Federation Brewery (and before that marketing director at Newcastle Breweries). It will be headed by Paul Currie (pictured above), co-founder of the award-winning Isle of Arran distillery. He said: &ldquo;The water is ideal, flowing from a source at Sprinkling Tarn &ndash; one of the most beautiful in Cumbria &ndash; through the foothills of Scafell Pike which are rich in peat, and will give the whisky a unique flavor and depth. Combine that with the purity of the air and you have the perfect raw ingredients for distilling whisky.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The distillery will be housed in a converted&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/our-distillery/our-buildings\">Victorian model farm</a>&nbsp;and aims to produce around 300,000 bottles of&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/brands/the-lakes-malt\">single malt whisky</a>&nbsp;per year with the creation of 27 jobs. The development of the site &ndash; with visitor centre,&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/distillery-bar-and-bistro\">bar, bistro</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/shop\">shop</a>&nbsp;&ndash; is scheduled to start this summer with plans to begin whisky production in December.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://cheersnortheast.co.uk/2013/06/lakes-dram-dream-takes-shape/\">By North East Cheers</a></p>',131),(32,32,'en','Coming Soon: LAKE DISTRICT WHISKY ','coming-soon-lake-district-whisky-3rd-june-2013','blog/Country_Life.jpg','Monday, 3rd June 2013','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Bassenthwaite is set to be the site of the first (legal) whisky distillery in the Lake District</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The Lake District is to have its first official whisky distillery. It will be housed in a converted&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/our-distillery/our-buildings\">Victorian model</a>&nbsp;farm on the edge of Bassenthwaite and should produce some 300,000 bottles of malt whisky a year.&nbsp;<br /><br />Paul Currie, co-founder of the Isle of Arran distillery, heads the consortium of investors. &lsquo;The water is ideal,\' he explains. &lsquo;It flows from a source at Sprinkling Tarn through the foothills of Scafell Pike, which are rich in peat and will give the whisky its flavour and depth. Combine that with the purity of the air, and you have the perfect raw ingredients for distilling whisky.\'</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In the 1800s, Cumbria, once part of Scotland, was rife with bootlegged whisky production thanks to the hilly terrain and abundance of rivers, but the new Lakes Distillery will be the first legal operation.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">By Nigel Burnham</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://www.countrylife.co.uk/news/article/531098/Coming-soon-Lake-District-Whisky.html\">Country Life</a></p>',131),(33,33,'en','NEW WHISKY DISTILLERY PLANNED FOR LAKE DISTRICT ','new-whisky-','blog/Harpers_2.jpg','Monday, 20th May 2013','<p>A new whisky distillery is set to open in the heart of the Lake District and will be the first in the region for more than 100 years.</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.harpers.co.uk/news/new-whisky-distillery-planned-for-lake-district/346877.article\">Read the article here</a></p>',131),(34,34,'en','For William Wordsworth, the Lake District was a national property for all to enjoy. But what the poet, a teetotal, would have made of the first whiskey distillery in the area for more than 100 years is hard to tell. The Lakes Distillery is set to open o','william-wordsw','blog/DSC_1046.jpg','For William Wordsworth, the Lake District was a national property for all to enjoy. But what the poet, a teetotal, would have made of the first whiskey distillery in the area for more than 100 years is hard to tell. The Lakes Distillery is set to open on the edge of the picturesque Bass','<p><strong>For William Wordsworth, the Lake District was a &ldquo;national property&rdquo; for all to enjoy. But what the poet, a teetotal, would have made of the first whiskey distillery in the area for more than 100 years is hard to tell.</strong></p>\r\n<p>The Lakes Distillery is set to open on the edge of the picturesque Bassenthwaite Lake in a converted<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/our-distillery/our-buildings\">Victorian model farm</a>. The &pound;2.5 million venture aims to produce around 300,000 bottles of&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/brands/the-lakes-malt\">single malt whisky</a>&nbsp;a year and create 27 jobs.</p>\r\n<p>A consortium of private investors, headed by Paul Currie, co-founder of the Isle of Arran distillery in Scotland, hope &nbsp;the distillery will be operational by December.</p>\r\n<p>Explaining the choice of location, Currie said: &ldquo;The water is ideal, flowing from a source at Sprinkling Tarn - one of the most beautiful tarns, or lakes, in Cumbria &ndash; through the foothills of Scafell Pike which are rich in peat and will give the whisky its unique flavour and depth. Combine that with the purity of the air and you have the perfect raw ingredients for distilling whisky.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;We are delighted to be bringing this ancient tradition back and are&nbsp;confident we will be able to produce an&nbsp;outstanding single malt.&nbsp; It is also our intention that the distillery will become one of the biggest tourist attractions in the Lakes.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>Despite stalling last year, Scotch whisky exports have increased dramatically over the past decade - up 190% to &pound;778m. An increasing percentage of which goes to emerging markets like China, keen for luxury products seen to hold status and heritage.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/food-and-drink/news/whiskey-distillery-to-open-in-the-heart-of-the-lake-district-8623079.html?origin=internalSearch\">By The Independant</a></p>',131),(35,35,'en','WHISKY IN THE LAKES','whisky-lakes','blog/imbibe.jpg','Tuesday, 14th May 2013','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Work has started on The Lakes Distillery, the first to grace the area in over a century, is set to open in Cumbria.</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The distillery will incorporate a&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/distillery-bar-and-bistro\">bar, bistro,</a>&nbsp;visitor centre and&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/shop\">shop</a>, and will be headed up by Paul Currie, one of the founders of the Isle of Arran Distillery.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Set within a&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/our-distillery/our-buildings\">Victorian farm</a>&nbsp;on the banks of Bassenthwaite Lake, custom-designed copper stills will be used, alongside a range of different casks such as bourbon barrels and sherry hogsheads and the water will be drawn from local source, Sprinkiling Tarn.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The distillery is aiming to produce 300,000 bottles per year, creating 27 jobs, and will also be producing a gin, made with local juniper, bilberries, heather and meadowsweet.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">There has also been a call for whisky buffs to join&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/members/founders-club\">The Founders\' Club</a>, for a one-off fee of &pound;595, which will entitle members to a series of special offers and perks, but most excitingly to an exclusive selection of whisky. The first 100 casks produced will be set aside, and then shared with them.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://imbibe.com/news/2013-05/whisky-in-the-lakes\">By Imbibe.com</a></p>',131),(37,37,'en','LAKES DISTILLERY TO PRODUCE ENGLISH WHISKY FROM DECEMBER ','lakes-distillery','blog/Drinks_International.jpg','Friday, 24th May 2013','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>The new &pound;2.5m Lakes Distillery will become the first whisky operation in the Lake District in more than 100 years, when it opens in December. The venture is backed by a consortium of private investors and headed by Paul Currie, co-founder of Isle of Arran distillery in western Scotland.</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Set on the edge of Bassenthwaite Lake, the distillery will be housed in a converted&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/our-distillery/our-buildings\">Victorian farm</a>and will produce around 300,000 bottles of lightly peated&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/brands/the-lakes-malt\">single malt&nbsp;</a>whisky per year, though the distillery&rsquo;s capacity will be one million bottles.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Plans are also afoot for a New World blend, made of whiskies from outside of Scotland.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Curry said: &ldquo;The water is ideal, flowing from a source at Sprinkling Tarn - one of the most beautiful tarns, or lakes, in Cumbria &ndash; through the foothills of Scafell Pike which are rich in peat and will give the whisky its unique flavor and depth. Combine that with the purity of the air and you have the perfect raw ingredients for distilling whisky.<br /><br />&ldquo;The area has a long history of illicit distilling as the fells provided an ideal location for hidden stills and smuggling, but is more than 100 years since the last whisky was produced here.\"</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The facility will use &ldquo; the latest industry technology&rdquo; including bespoke copper pot stills.<br /><br />The first 100 casks produced at the distillery will be bottled for members of the<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/members/founders-club\">&nbsp;Founders&rsquo; Club</a>, an initiative designed to attract whisky enthusiasts to the brand.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Currie added: &ldquo;Imagine if you could have bought one of the first bottles of one the great single malts. It&rsquo;s going to be fascinating seeing how our spirit matures and we want&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/members/connoisseurs-club\">connoisseurs</a>&nbsp;and friends of the Lakes to be part of the journey.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Along with the distillery the site will house a visitor centre &ndash; that offers&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/our-distillery/distillery-tours\">tours</a>&nbsp;of the site - a&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/distillery-bar-and-bistro\">bar, bistro</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/shop\">shop</a>, aimed at showcasing locally-sourced Cumbrian produce.<br /><br />Further investment is also sought by the consortium to fund &ldquo;future development&rdquo;.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">By&nbsp;Hamish Smith</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://www.drinksint.com/news/fullstory.php/aid/3836/Lakes_Distillery_to_produce_English_whisky_from_December.html\">Drinks International</a></p>',131),(38,38,'en','LAKE\'S FIRST DISTILLERY IN A CENTURY TO OPEN ','lakes-first-distillery-century-open-20th-may-2013','blog/Insider_Media.jpg','Monday, 20th May 2013','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Almost 30 jobs are to be created at new &pound;2.5m whisky distillery in the Lake District &ndash; the area\'s first for more than a century.</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Work on the conversion of a<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/our-distillery/our-buildings\">&nbsp;Victorian farm</a>&nbsp;plot is due to commence later this summer with brewing operations scheduled for a December start.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Called the Lakes Distillery, it will be housed in a 15,000 sq ft building on eight acres of land on the edge of Bassenthwaite Lake, near Cockermouth.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">It will initially employ 27 staff and aim to produce 300,000 bottles per year.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Along with the distillery, the site will house a visitor centre with a&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/distillery-bar-and-bistro\">bar, bistro</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/shop\">shop</a>.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Paul Currie, who co-founded the Isle of Arran distillery in Scotland, is leading the project with a team of private investors.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">He said: \"The water is ideal, flowing from a source at Sprinkling Tarn through the foothills of Scafell Pike which are rich in peat and will give the whisky its unique flavour and depth.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\"Combine that with the purity of the air and you have the perfect raw ingredients for distilling whisky.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\"The area has a long history of illicit distilling as the fells provided an ideal location for hidden stills and smuggling but it is more than 100 years since the last whisky was produced here.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\"We are delighted to be bringing this ancient tradition back and are confident we will be able to produce an outstanding&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/brands/the-lakes-malt\">single malt.</a></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\"It is also our intention that the distillery will become one of the biggest tourist attractions in the Lakes.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://www.insidermedia.com/insider/north-west/90536-\">Insider Media</a></p>',131),(39,39,'en','NEW LAKE DISTRICT WHISKY DISTILLERY LAUNCHES FOUNDERS CLUB','new-lake-district-whisky-distillery','blog/The_Spirits_Business_2.jpg','Wednesday, 15th May 2013','<p><strong>A new English whisky distillery has launched a&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/members/founders-club\">Founders&rsquo; Club</a>&nbsp;to help raise funds prior to distillation starting next year.</strong></p>\r\n<p>The Lakes Distillery will start producing liquid in 2014.</p>\r\n<p>The Lakes Distillery, the first whisky distillery to open in England&rsquo;s Lake District in over a century, is giving consumers the chance to own some of its first bottles of whisky, as well as other special offers and discounts, for a one-off payment of &pound;595. The first 100 casks produced each year will also be set aside exclusively for&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/members/founders-club\">Founders&rsquo; Club</a>&nbsp;members.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;It&rsquo;s a fantastic opportunity,&rdquo; said Paul Currie, co-founder of the Isle of Arran distillery in Scotland and founder of the Lakes Distillery. &ldquo;I am confident that the whisky we produce here will be among the finest in the world for a number of reasons.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Our water flows from a source at Sprinkling Tarn &ndash; one of the most beautiful tarns, or lakes, in Cumbria &ndash; through the foothills of Scafell Pike which are rich in peat and will give the whisky its unique flavor and depth. &nbsp;Combine that with the purity of the air and you have the perfect raw ingredients for distilling whisky.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>The &pound;2.5m distillery is being built at the site of a former&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/our-distillery/our-buildings\">Victorian farm</a>&nbsp;at the edge of Bassenthwaite Lake in the National Park itself, which in the 1800s was rich with illicit whisky production thanks to the area&rsquo;s hilly terrain and abundance of rivers.</p>\r\n<p>The farm buildings will contain two stills with a relatively small capacity of 3,500 litres designed to produce a lighter style whisky. Currie is joined by former Diageo whisky bod Alan Rutherford,&nbsp;who will oversee production.</p>\r\n<p>Development of the site is due to take pace this autumn, with production kicking off in summer 2014. While Currie waits for the whisky to mature, it will produce<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/brands/the-lakes-gin\">Lakes Gin</a>&nbsp;from a third, smaller pot still using local botanicals.</p>\r\n<p>With 18 million visitors passing through the National Park every year, Lakes Distillery will have its visitors&rsquo; centre up and running by the end of 2013.</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.thespiritsbusiness.com/2013/05/new-lake-district-whisky-distillery-launches-founders-club/\">The Spirits Business</a></p>',131),(40,40,'en','WORK TO START ON 1.5M KESWICK DISTILLERY  6TH APRIL 2013','work-star','blog/DSC04149.jpg','Saturday, 6th April 2013','<p><strong>Building work is due to start on the site of a &pound;1.5 million distillery near Keswick. Paul Currie is behind plans to renovate a Victorian farm, near Bassenthwaite, to produce Cumbria&rsquo;s first whisky and gin.</strong></p>\r\n<p>He said the plant itself had now been ordered and building work is due to start in the next two months.</p>\r\n<p>Mr Currie, who set up a distillery on the Isle of Arran 15 years ago, got permission for the conversion in 2011.</p>\r\n<p>He plans to set up the Lakes Distillery at Low Barkhouse Farm together with a visitor centre, including&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/our-distillery/distillery-tours\">tours</a>, a&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/shop\">shop</a>&nbsp;and a&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/distillery-bar-and-bistro\">bar &amp; bistro</a>.</p>\r\n<p>It is expected that the distillery will produce 100,000 litres of whisky a year plus the county&rsquo;s first branded&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/brands/the-lakes-gin\">gin</a>.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;The location could not be better,&rdquo; he said.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;The peaty water from the fells will blend nicely to create a wonderful taste that will appeal.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>The distillery will contain two stills for the production of whisky, one wash and one spirit.</p>\r\n<p>They will have a capacity of 3,500 litres and are currently being built in Scotland.</p>\r\n<p>Mr Currie said there would be a third small still in the still house which will produce the only Lakes gin on the market, using local juniper berries.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;There is no reason why we cannot create a brand that goes global because we have all the right ingredients,&rdquo; he said.</p>\r\n<p>Mr Currie said there was a heritage of whisky in Cumbria in the past but &ldquo;not all of it was legal!&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;It&rsquo;s a tradition we&rsquo;d like to revive and spread to the masses,&rdquo; he said.</p>\r\n<p>He hopes to capitalise on the county&rsquo;s strong tourism trade and said visitors could also experience Bassenthwaite lake and Keswick.</p>\r\n<p>He said he hoped to open the visitor centre at the end of 2013, with production of whisky and gin starting around the same time.</p>',131),(41,41,'en','CALL FOR INVESTORS FOR NEW LAKE DISTRICT DISTILLERY','call-investors-for-new-lakes-distillery','blog/Harpers_1.jpg','Thursday, 17th January 2013','<p><span>Further investment is being sought for a &pound;2.5-million new distillery, The Lakes Distillery, which is to be built in Cumbria and opened at the back end of 2013.</span></p>\r\n<p><span> http://www.harpers.co.uk/news/call-for-investors-for-new-lake-district-distillery/313365.article</span></p>',131),(43,43,'en','RETAIL KING NIGEL MILLS SETS SIGHTS ON NEW WHISKY EMPIRE ','retail-king-nigel-mills-sets-sights-on-whisky-empi','blog/The_Journal_2.jpg','Wednesday, 16th January 2013','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>THE man behind the North East\'s biggest independent chain of shops has his sights set on making whisky in the Lake District.</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Nigel Mills, who founded the Whitley Bay-based Mills Group before selling the business to Tesco for more than &pound;20m in 2011, hopes to repeat the success with a new venture in Cumbria.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The &pound;2.5m Lakes Distillery on a farm near Bassenthwaite Lake has received planning permission and building will commence in April this year.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The distillery should create 25 jobs and, although no whisky will be available until matured for at least three years, the company hopes to start selling their Cumbrian-made&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/brands/the-lakes-gin\">gin&nbsp;</a>by April 2014.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Mills is joined in his latest venture by Paul Currie, who set up the Isle of Arran distillery with his father 15 years ago.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Mills said: &ldquo;We&rsquo;ve put a board together comprising myself, Paul, Geoff Hodgson, my former finance director at Mills Group, Martin Stokoe, and Gary Thornton.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&ldquo;We&rsquo;re managing to raise between &pound;1m and &pound;2m and we&rsquo;ve also received some European grant funding to get the business started.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&ldquo;We&rsquo;re hoping to open the visitor centre,&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/distillery-bar-and-bistro\">bar and bistro</a>&nbsp;and local art gallery by April 2014.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&ldquo;It will be one of the biggest tourist attractions in Cumbria when it&rsquo;s established and create jobs in a national park that desperately needs employment.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&ldquo;There is only one other whisky distillery in England and that&rsquo;s in Norfolk but it is very much a smaller operation to what we are trying to do in the Lake District.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Cumbria has a heritage for whisky-making as it was a Celtic area and whisky was distilled illegally there until late into the 19th Century.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The landscape is one of fast-flowing rivers, rugged mountains and clean pure air. These conditions are very much like those found in Scotland, and they are ideal for producing malt whisky.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">There is also a long history of illicit whisky distilling in the area, with the secluded hills and valleys of the area ideal for smugglers.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">One of these distillers was Lancelot &lsquo;Lanty&rsquo; Slee, who had a thriving business and always managed to keep one step ahead of the customs authorities, helped by supplying his whisky to the local magistrates.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The Lakes Distillery will set aside the first 100 casks produced and, each year, will bottle the maturing whisky exclusively for its&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/members/founders-club\">Founders&rsquo; Club</a>&nbsp;members.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Each year for 10 years, members will receive one 70cl bottle plus two miniatures, giving them the opportunity to taste the spirit as it develops over time into a 10-year-old malt whisky. These casks will not be available to the general public &ndash; only to members.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&ldquo;We will sell the whisky through our membership club, the distillery and distribute it around the world,&rdquo; said Mills. &ldquo;We don&rsquo;t want to produce huge volumes as we want it to remain a niche product.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&ldquo;You&rsquo;ll be able to distinguish it from Scottish whiskies as it will be distilled three times instead of twice. We aim to produce roughly 24,000 casks a year each containing 12 bottles.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&ldquo;All of us involved bring a lot of business experience to the table, and although it&rsquo;s still very much a commercial venture for all of us, it&rsquo;s also a great deal of fun.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://www.thejournal.co.uk/business/business-news/retail-king-nigel-mills-sets-4398206\">The Journal</a></p>',131),(44,44,'en','LAKE DISTRICT WHISKY DISTILLERY TO CREATE 27 JOBS NEXT YEAR - 21ST SEPTEMBER 2012','lake-district-whisky-','blog/DSC04126.jpg','A new whisky distillery near Cockermouth is due to open next summer, creating 27 jobs. Building work on The Lakes Distillery at Low Barkhouse Farm in Setmurthy is likely to start in the next few months. The Lakes Distillery Company was given the go-ahead by Lake District planners last yea','<p><strong>A new whisky distillery near Cockermouth is due to open next summer, creating 27 jobs.</strong></p>\r\n<p>Building work on The Lakes Distillery at Low Barkhouse Farm in Setmurthy is likely to start in the next few months.</p>\r\n<p>The Lakes Distillery Company was given the go-ahead by Lake District planners last year, despite the scheme being recommended for refusal by planning officers.</p>\r\n<p>Building work was due to start late last year with hopes it opening in June.</p>\r\n<p>Paul Currie, founder and managing director of The Lakes Distillery Company, said this week: &ldquo;Building work has been delayed because there were a few things we had to finalise as regards to the building work.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;The Victorian building, which the distillery will be housed in, is 150 years old and we hope that it will attract a lot of local interest.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;We will be producing&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/brands/the-lakes-malt\">lakes malt</a>&nbsp;whisky and&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/brands/the-lakes-gin\">gins</a>&nbsp;using local botanicals.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>The distillery will also run a visitor centre, including&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/our-distillery/distillery-tours\">tours</a>, a shop and a&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/distillery-bar-and-bistro\">bar &amp; bistro</a>.</p>',131),(45,45,'en','LAKE DISTRICT WHISKY DISTILLERY TO CREATE 27 JOBS NEXT YEAR - 21ST SEPTEMBER 2012','lake-district-whisky-','blog/DSC04126_1.jpg','A new whisky distillery near Cockermouth is due to open next summer, creating 27 jobs. Building work on The Lakes Distillery at Low Barkhouse Farm in Setmurthy is likely to start in the next few months. The Lakes Distillery Company was given the go-ahead by Lake District planners last yea','<p><strong>A new whisky distillery near Cockermouth is due to open next summer, creating 27 jobs.</strong></p>\r\n<p>Building work on The Lakes Distillery at Low Barkhouse Farm in Setmurthy is likely to start in the next few months.</p>\r\n<p>The Lakes Distillery Company was given the go-ahead by Lake District planners last year, despite the scheme being recommended for refusal by planning officers.</p>\r\n<p>Building work was due to start late last year with hopes it opening in June.</p>\r\n<p>Paul Currie, founder and managing director of The Lakes Distillery Company, said this week: &ldquo;Building work has been delayed because there were a few things we had to finalise as regards to the building work.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;The Victorian building, which the distillery will be housed in, is 150 years old and we hope that it will attract a lot of local interest.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;We will be producing&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/brands/the-lakes-malt\">lakes malt</a>&nbsp;whisky and&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/brands/the-lakes-gin\">gins</a>&nbsp;using local botanicals.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>The distillery will also run a visitor centre, including&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/our-distillery/distillery-tours\">tours</a>, a shop and a&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/distillery-bar-and-bistro\">bar &amp; bistro</a>.</p>',131),(46,46,'en','WHISKY INSIDERS INTERVIEW - PAUL CURRIE','whisky-ins','blog/The_Whisky_Wire.jpg','Wednesday, 30th January 2013','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">How long have you been working in the whisky industry?</span></strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">I started in 1995 when I set up Arran Distillers with my father. My new venture is now to set up a distillery in the Lake District, the Lakes Distillery, which will open this year. As well as a&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/brands/the-lakes-malt\">single malt</a>, we&rsquo;ll also be producing&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/brands/the-lakes-gin\">gin</a>.<br /><br /><strong><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">What has been your biggest career highlight to date?</span></strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Up until now it has to be the day Arran opened, although I expect this to be surpassed when we start production at our new Lakes Distillery in Cumbria. For me this will be a greater achievement, to start a new distillery in a new whisky region, which has a long heritage of illicit whisky production in the past.<br /><br /><strong><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Can you remember your first dram, and indeed what it was?</span></strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">My father spent his working life in the industry, so I grew up with whisky coursing through my veins. I probably had several tiny sips as a toddler, but the first I can remember was when I was 16 with an Aberlour.<br /><br /><strong><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">What does whisky mean to you?</span></strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Whisky is an extraordinary product, with an uncanny ability to bring a sense of goodwill and good humour to those who enjoy it. It&rsquo;s wonderful to be involved with something that holds such a fascination to so many people.<br /><br /><strong><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Where would you like to see yourself in five years time?</span></strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">I would hope by then that the Lakes Distillery is becoming well established, and that we are producing a whisky recognised as being of the highest quality.<br /><br /><strong><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">What was your last dram?</span></strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">An Arran 14 year old yesterday evening, wonderful!<br /><br /><strong><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Do you have a favourite whisky and food pairing combination?</span></strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">I am very partial to a combination of herrings and whisky, although I think you can drink whisky with almost any food.<br /><br /><strong><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">What&rsquo;s your favourite time and place to enjoy a dram?</span></strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Any place with good friends, whisky is much better shared! I also look forward later this year to climbing Skiddaw (fourth highest fell in the Lakes, very near our new Lakes Distillery) and to celebrating our opening with a dram at the summit.<br /><br /><strong><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">What do you think is going to be the next big thing on the whisky horizon?</span></strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">I think there will continue to be more new &lsquo;artisan&rsquo; distilleries opening just as we are doing with the Lakes Distillery. There will also be increasing innovation, particularly to find new ways of attracting younger consumers.<br /><br /><strong><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">What&rsquo;s the one dram you couldn&rsquo;t live without?</span></strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Of course it will be the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/brands/the-lakes-malt\">Lakes Malt!</a></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://www.thewhiskywire.com/2012/01/whisky-insiders-interview-paul-currie.html\">The Whisky Wire</a></p>',131),(47,47,'en','MEET THE MAN WHO PLANS TO BRING WHISKY DISTILLING BACK TO CUMBRIA - 4TH OCTOBER 2011','meet-man-w','blog/PC_10.jpg','Meet Paul Currie, the 49-year-old entrepreneur whose focus is to make Cumbrian whisky the envy of the world. Mr Currie plans the 1.5m transformation of a dilapidated farm at Setmurthy, near Cockermouth, to create the perfect environment to blend a Lakes Malt whisky. Picturesque surround','<p><strong>Meet Paul Currie, the 49-year-old entrepreneur whose focus is to make Cumbrian whisky the envy of the world.</strong></p>\r\n<p>Mr Currie plans the &pound;1.5m transformation of a dilapidated farm at Setmurthy, near Cockermouth, to create the perfect environment to blend a&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/brands/the-lakes-malt\">Lakes Malt&nbsp;</a>whisky.</p>\r\n<p>Picturesque surroundings, pure peaty water from the River Derwent and a tried and trusted recipe will go into reviving the industry in Cumbria.</p>\r\n<p>For now, old barns with wooden beams stand among weeds and waste left behind when Low Barkhouse Farm stopped being worked.</p>\r\n<p>But by the turn of the year, Mr Currie says, the area will be transformed.</p>\r\n<p>Planning permission for the work was recently granted.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;The location could not be better,&rdquo; said Mr Currie, who set up a successful distillery on the Isle of Arran with his father Harold 15 years ago.</p>\r\n<p>He added: &ldquo;Work to transform one of the barns into a visitor centre will start by the end of the year because it is important to start generating money for the local economy.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;We want to keep the traditional beams and the quirkiness of the buildings because it shows character that a new-build could never.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;The stonework is in great condition but we will need to work on the roofs to make sure they are safe.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;It&rsquo;s the perfect place to distill whisky and I&rsquo;m excited about the future.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;It will take time before the whisky is ready but the end product will be a smooth blend that&rsquo;s golden in colour.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>Mr Currie aims to create a global brand which, at first, will produce 240,000 bottles of&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/brands/the-lakes-malt\">Lakes Malt</a>.</p>\r\n<p>He said: &ldquo;A lot of people have asked me why I chose Cumbria to set up base and the answer is &lsquo;why not?&rsquo;.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;When you say the words &lsquo;Cumbrian whisky&rsquo; it doesn&rsquo;t sound daft does it? In fact it makes perfect sense.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;There is no reason why we cannot create a brand that goes global because we have all the right ingredients.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;The peaty water from the fells will blend nicely to create a wonderful taste that will appeal.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;There&rsquo;s a heritage of whisky in Cumbria. Not all of it was legal, but it&rsquo;s a tradition we&rsquo;d like to revive and spread to the masses.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;The aim has to be turn this distillery into a global brand. We are in an area of the country where tourism rules. At Setmurthy the distillery will be based near the beautiful Bassenthwaite Lake, with Keswick and its tourist attractions close by too.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;West Cumbria is a great place to base a business because of the tourism and its beautiful scenery.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>It will take 10 years before the first bottle of malt is put on the shelves and, until it&rsquo;s ready, Mr Currie will produce&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/brands/the-lakes-gin\">gin</a>&nbsp;as well as running a visitor centre.</p>\r\n<p>Mr Currie, who graduated from Bristol University, worked for oil firm BP for eight years.</p>\r\n<p>Based mainly in Eastern Europe setting up new businesses for them, he quit to start the Arran distillery with his dad.</p>',131),(48,48,'en','25 JOBS CREATED AS NEW CUMBRIAN WHISKY DISTILLERY GETS GO-AHEAD - 15TH SEPTEMBER 2011','25-jobs-created-','blog/Lakes_Distillery_Buildings.jpg','The ancient tradition of whisky distilling is to be revived in Cumbria  but this time it will be legal. Planning permission has been granted for a 1.5 million conversion of Low Barkhouse Farm, a former Victorian model farm, at Setmurthy, near Bassenthwaite Lake. The Lakes Distillery','<p><strong>The ancient tradition of whisky distilling is to be revived in Cumbria &ndash; but this time it will be legal.</strong></p>\r\n<p>Planning permission has been granted for a &pound;1.5 million conversion of Low Barkhouse Farm, a former Victorian model farm, at Setmurthy, near Bassenthwaite Lake.</p>\r\n<p>The Lakes Distillery will create 25 jobs when it opens next summer, according to managing director Paul Currie.</p>\r\n<p>He and his father set up a successful distillery on the Isle of Arran 15 years ago and he turned his attentions to Cumbria because of its peaty water.</p>\r\n<p>Mr Currie, 49, said: &ldquo;It&rsquo;s ideal for whisky making. If you look back at the history of Cumbria, it was a Celtic area and whisky was distilled illegally here until late into the 19th century.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;The conditions are very like Scotland.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>A 10-year-old&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/brands/the-lakes-malt\">single malt</a>&nbsp;would become the flagship product of the distillery but until that is ready, the site will also make gin to generate cash flow.</p>\r\n<p>There will be a visitor centre, cafe and shop and the first 100 casks of the malt whisky will be set aside for members of a&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/members/founders-club\">founders&rsquo; club</a>.</p>\r\n<p>It took Mr Currie 18 months to find a suitable site in Cumbria and a lengthy planning process then ensued.</p>\r\n<p>The Lake District National Park development control committee recently approved the development against advice from its officers because of objections from local residents.</p>\r\n<p>The committee passed the development after a site visit.</p>\r\n<p>The historic<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/our-distillery/our-buildings\">&nbsp;model farm buildings</a>&nbsp;had fallen into disuse. Work will start to transform them within a few months.</p>\r\n<p>Mr Currie added: &ldquo;It will be 10 years before the product appears in shops.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>Cash for renovations has come from whisky-loving private investors.</p>\r\n<p>One of the biggest investments will be made on equipment including traditional copper stills.</p>\r\n<p>Some Cumbrian barley will be used to make the whisky.</p>\r\n<p>Once fully up and running, the distillery would produce 240,000 bottles of Lakes Malt every year.</p>\r\n<p>By Anna Burdett&nbsp;</p>',131),(49,49,'en','PLANS TO CREATE A CUMBRIAN WHISKY DISTILLERY - 28TH APRIL 2011','plans-create-cumbria','blog/Sprinkling_Tarn_1.jpg','','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Plans are in the pipeline to open a whisky distillery near Cockermouth, creating up to 25 jobs.</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Cumbria Distillers Limited plans to create a Cumbrian whisky region with the launch of a distillery at Setmurthy, which will make a single&nbsp;<a href=\"http://213.175.215.219/~lakes2/brands/the-lakes-malt\">Lakes Malt</a>&nbsp;whisky.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The firm said the worldwide whisky market was booming, with sales up 10 per cent over the last year and generating &pound;3.5 billion.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The highest growth has been in sales of malt whisky, up by 18 per cent, which has encouraged the opening of several new distilleries in Scotland and England.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The new venture aims to take advantage of the drink&rsquo;s rising popularity.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The firm has lodged plans with the Lake District National Park Authority.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Paul Currie, Cumbria Distillers founder and managing director, said the county&rsquo;s history included tales of many illicit whisky distillers.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">He said: &ldquo;The Lake District, with its similarities to Scotland, is considered ideal for making malt whisky.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&ldquo;The area has many Celtic roots, and illicit stills were operating in the region in the 17th and 18th centuries.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&ldquo;With abundant water, local barley and ideal conditions for maturing the whisky, we&rsquo;re confident of producing a world-class malt.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&ldquo;We aim to be open by this time next year, producing around 20,000 cases of 12 bottles a year.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A distiller from Arran will be involved in setting up the operation but the firm will recruit locally, probably from the brewing trade.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Most of the whisky will be sold after 10 years of maturation, similar to quality Highlands whisky.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The business will be accommodated within former agricultural buildings, which were constructed as a Victorian model farm.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Mr Currie said the 9,000 sq ft site was ideal for a small artisan distillery.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A planning application is due to be considered by national park authority at a meeting of its development control committee.</p>',131),(50,50,'en','WHISKY DISTILLERY PLAN FOR FORMER CUMBRIA LAKE DISTRICT FARM - 28TH APRIL 2011','whisky-distillery-plan-fo','','The county has long been known for the quality of its many home-grown beers, with local breweries producing distinctive ales that have been acclaimed worldwide. And there are now plans to create a Cumbrian whisky region with the launch of a distillery at Setmurthy, near Cockermouth, which wil','<p>Plans to create a Cumbrian whisky region with the launch of a distillery at Setmurthy, near Cockermouth, which will make a single malt whisky.</p>\r\n<p>The county has long been known for the quality of its many home-grown beers, with local breweries producing distinctive ales that have been acclaimed worldwide.</p>\r\n<p>And there are now plans to create a Cumbrian whisky region with the launch of a distillery at Setmurthy, near Cockermouth, which will make a single malt whisky.</p>\r\n<p>Cumbria Distilleries Limited, the firm involved, says the worldwide whisky market is booming, with sales up 10 per cent over the last year and generating &pound;3.5 billion.</p>\r\n<p>The highest growth has been in the sales of malt whisky, up by 18 per cent, which has encouraged the opening of several new distilleries both in both Scotland and England.</p>\r\n<p>This new venture &ndash; which will make Lakes Malt &ndash; aims to take advantage of the drink&rsquo;s rising popularity.</p>\r\n<p>The plans, now lodged with the Lake District National Park Authority, are being guided by the founder of a successful distillery on the Isle of Arran 15 years ago.</p>\r\n<p>Cumbria Distillers founder and managing director Paul Currie said the county&rsquo;s history included tales of many illicit whisky distillers.</p>\r\n<p>He said: &ldquo;The Lake District, with its similarities to Scotland, is considered ideal for making malt whisky.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;The area has many Celtic roots, and illicit stills were operating in the region in the 17th and 18th centuries,&rsquo;</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;With abundant water, local barley and ideal conditions for maturing the whisky, we&rsquo;re confident of producing a world-class malt. We aim to be open by this time next year, producing around 20,000 cases of 12 bottles a year.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>A distiller from Arran will be involved in setting up the operation but the firm will recruit locally, probably from the brewing trade.</p>\r\n<p>Most of the whisky will be sold after 10 years of maturation, similar to quality Highlands whisky.</p>\r\n<p>The business will be accommodated within former agricultural buildings, which were originally constructed as a Victorian model farm.</p>\r\n<p>Mr Currie said the site is ideal for a small artisan distillery.</p>\r\n<p>The business is expected to employ up to 25 people.</p>\r\n<p>A planning application is due to be considered by the Lake District National Park Authority at a future meeting of their development control committee.</p>\r\n<p>By Phil Coleman&nbsp;</p>',131),(52,52,'en','Online alcohol sales surge set to continue, say analyists','online-alcohol-sales-surge-set-continue','blog/The_Grocer.jpg','After a festive surge in online alcohol sales, analysts are forecasting an even stronger 2014 than 2013.','<p><a href=\"http://www.thegrocer.co.uk/fmcg/online-alcohol-sales-surge-set-to-continue-say-analysts/353634.article\">http://www.thegrocer.co.uk/fmcg/online-alcohol-sales-surge-set-to-continue-say-analysts/353634.article</a></p>',132),(53,53,'en','English distillers race to profit from the 4bn whisky boom ','english-distillers-race-profit-4bn-whisky-boom','blog/The_Telegraph.jpg','Sunday, 9th February 2014','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">English whisky was off the menu for more than a century. Now five entrepreneurs are battling to cash in on a revival, writes Tom Rowley.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">From the moment Paul Currie&rsquo;s father first took him to a distillery at the age of six, he was entranced by the steaming copper stills. He took his first sip of Scotch (very small, he insists) at 11, and was hooked by his late teens. Now, aged 49, he is finally on the cusp of making his own &ndash; in England.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Next week, a team of 30 builders will begin work on a &pound;4 million project to transform a Victorian farm in the Lake District into Mr Currie&rsquo;s distillery. When it begins making spirit in June, it will be England&rsquo;s biggest whisky distillery, producing up to 1 million bottles a year.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Yet until five years ago, English whisky had been off the menu for more than a century, since the Lea Valley distillery in London closed in 1903. Now connoisseurs and investors are racing to establish new distilleries, in an attempt to benefit from surging worldwide demand for single malts.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In 2012, &pound;4.3 billion of Scotch was sold overseas, accounting for around a quarter of all UK food and drink exports. The value of Scotch exports has risen 87 percent in a decade, and English rivals are keen to take a slice of this lucrative trade. Mr Currie is the fifth entrepreneur to set up a distillery south of the border in the last eight years.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Dominic Roskrow, director of the Craft Distillers Alliance and a former editor of Whisky magazine, believes the number of English distilleries could now quadruple. &ldquo;We have suddenly seen an explosion in whisky and England is at the forefront of it,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;Over the next two years, we will see more and more people looking to do it.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">For now, there is little sign of this revolution at Low Barkhouse Farm. Nestled beneath the snow-capped peak of Skiddaw, England&rsquo;s fourth highest mountain, rotting chairs and smashed concrete cattle stalls litter the 1850s outbuildings of The Lakes Distillery. Piles of hay line the floor of the barn, untouched since the dairy farm was abandoned 20 years ago. Cobwebs cling to every inch of the Cumbrian stone walls.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&ldquo;By the end of the year, this will be incredible,&rdquo; insisted Mr Currie. In April, a crane will lift three stills &ndash; two for whisky and one for gin and vodka &ndash; into the barn. But it will be another three years until the first spirit can officially be called whisky, and at least two more until it is ready to be sold.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&ldquo;We&rsquo;re going to avoid bottling it too young, although it is very tempting to get the product out there,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;We&rsquo;ll hold back. It will have been much in the making.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Of course, the spirit will not technically be Scotch: EU legislation only allows the label to be applied to whisky made entirely in Scotland. The taste will be familiar to Scotch lovers, however, because it will be matured in a similar environment.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Mr Currie first decided to set up a distillery on a holiday in the Lakes with his three teenagers five years ago. &ldquo;As soon as I saw this landscape, I thought &lsquo;this looks like Scotland&rsquo; &ndash; it looks like whisky country,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;The water we get here is very similar to Scotland.&rdquo; The River Derwent flows down from its source, Sprinkling Tarn, high in the fells, through peaty foothills to the farm, ensuring that the water will be lightly peated. &ldquo;There are damp conditions here, which also helps. When you are maturing whisky, you don&rsquo;t want it too hot because it will evaporate.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Andrew Nelstrop established the first in the new generation of distilleries in 2005, when he set up his English Whisky Company in Norfolk. The farmer planned merely to experiment by turning some of his excess barley crop into whisky. Instead, he was soon making 150,000 bottles a year. &ldquo;It went from being a fun thing to have a go at to a massive business,&rdquo; he said. Marks and Spencer began selling its own-label English whisky, distilled by Mr Nelstrop, last October. The company would have grown even faster if only it did not have to wait five years to mature more stock.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Two established brewers &ndash; Adnams and Hicks and Healey &ndash; have since experimented with English whisky. Darren Rook, CEO of the London Distillery Company in Battersea, filled his first cask of whisky before Christmas, and soon expects to produce 600 bottles a week.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The bulk of this English whisky will be exported to Asia and Latin America, where demand is growing rapidly. Mr Currie expects nine in ten bottles to be shipped overseas. He will visit Asia for a fortnight next month, where he hopes to take orders from countries such as Singapore, Taiwan, South Korea and China. Within four years, he plans to be trading in 40 countries.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&ldquo;In Asia, the emerging middle classes are looking to buy it,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;Whisky is an aspirational product and it is a status thing. If I can have this whisky, it shows everyone that I can afford it.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Demand is also rapidly increasing in Mexico, Brazil and Venezuela, where the spirit is appealing to younger drinkers. The average whisky drinker in Mexico is just 23. &ldquo;We&rsquo;re really keen to move away from that pipe and tweed image,&rdquo; said Mr Currie. &ldquo;It can be a much more fashionable drink. On our website we&rsquo;ve got a series of videos of cocktails you can make with it.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">According to Dominic Roskrow, English whisky is better placed than Scotch to tap into this trend. &ldquo;Because it&rsquo;s English, the baggage that goes with that old man image some people have of Scotch goes out the window,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;In Mad Men [the slick US drama set in a Fifties advertising agency], the characters were regularly seen to be drinking single malt &ndash; that is a great association.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Even so, many of the new distilleries rely on expertise from north of the border. Paul Currie used to run a distillery on the Isle of Arran with his father, Harold, and his master distiller, Chris Anderson, was born on Islay, and spent four decades producing Scotch.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">But Scotch distillers are untroubled by the threat from the English upstarts. &ldquo;They have recognised the fantastic growth that is out there and they want to get in on it,&rdquo; said David Frost, chief executive of the Scotch Whisky Association. &ldquo;All our firms thrive on the competition &ndash; and we&rsquo;ll beat it.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://www.telegraph.co.uk/foodanddrink/foodanddrinknews/10624038/English-distillers-race-to-profit-from-the-4bn-whisky-boom.html#disqus_thread\">The Sunday Telegraph</a></p>',131),(54,54,'en','Marks and Spencer Fine Single Malt English Whisky out-sold Scottish bottles','fine-single-malt-english-whisky-out-sold-scott','blog/Daily_Mail_1.jpg','English dram outsells Scotch: Distillers believe growth in sales could be boosted due to independence vote','<p>Performance of English variety hailed as &lsquo;coup&rsquo; for industry south of border</p>\r\n<p>Distillers believe demand driven as Scots prepare to vote for independence</p>\r\n<p>Scotland\'s traditional whisky distilleries are facing a spirited fight... from England</p>\r\n<p>Scotland&rsquo;s traditional whisky distilleries are facing a spirited fight... from England.</p>\r\n<p>Sales figures revealed by Marks and Spencer showed the chain&rsquo;s Fine Single Malt English Whisky out-sold its new Scottish Single Malt by two to one during the Christmas period.</p>\r\n<p>Both bottles have been on sale for &pound;35 - and the impressive performance of the English variety is being hailed as a &lsquo;coup&rsquo; for the fledgling industry south of the border.</p>\r\n<p>Distillers believe a growing &lsquo;English movement&rsquo; - as the Scots prepare to vote for independence - could have helped boost sales.</p>\r\n<p>M&amp;S&rsquo;s English Whisky is made by St George&rsquo;s Distillery, in Roudham, Norfolk, which was set up in 2006 and is currently the only distillery in England - though several others are now being developed.</p>\r\n<p>Andrew Nelstrop, managing director of the English Whisky Company Limited, which runs St George&rsquo;s Distillery, said he was &lsquo;delighted&rsquo; at the sales figures.</p>\r\n<p>&lsquo;We weren&rsquo;t expecting to outsell Scottish whisky. It&rsquo;s a very nice feeling,&rsquo; he said.</p>\r\n<p>&lsquo;We produce a range of different whisky types, from the malty to the more heathery varieties. The one we did for M&amp;S is a bespoke single malt with a bit of smoke, which is easy to drink.</p>\r\n<p>&lsquo;These kind of sales show people aren&rsquo;t just buying our whisky as a novelty to see what English whisky tastes like but must be coming back for second bottles - meaning it&rsquo;s been well-received.&rsquo;</p>\r\n<p>Mr Nelstrop, a farmer before setting up his distillery, says the business is only &lsquo;tiny&rsquo; compared with some of the Scottish distilleries - employing just two production and two office staff.</p>\r\n<p>But he said the industry is a &lsquo;growing sector&rsquo;.</p>\r\n<p>Sales figures revealed by Marks and Spencer showed the chain\'s Fine Single Malt English Whisky out-sold its new Scottish Single Malt by two to one during the Christmas period</p>\r\n<p>&lsquo;We were the first English distillery for 100 years but a second is just getting going elsewhere, and four more are being developed,&rsquo; Mr Nelstrop said.</p>\r\n<p>He added that the Scottish independence referendum may have encouraged some whisky drinkers south of the border to try his product instead.</p>\r\n<p>Emma Dawson, spirits buyer for M&amp;S, said: &lsquo;We are all about innovation and new offerings; an approach which is made possible by the confidence we have in our customers to be adventurous.&rsquo;</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2553468/English-dram-outsells-Scotch-Distillers-believe-growth-sales-boosted-independence-vote.html\">The Daily Mail</a></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>',132),(55,55,'en','The Lakes Distillery Set to Send Whisky to France','lakes-distillery-set-send-whisky-france','blog/In-Cumbria.jpg','Tuesday, 11 February 2014\r\n\r\n','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The Lakes Distillery is preparing to begin exports to France from April.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Although the distillery &ndash; at Setmurthy near Bassenthwaite &ndash; is not due to start production until later this year, it launched its first whisky at the Taste Cumbria food festival in Cockermouth in September.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><br />The One is a blend of grain and malt whiskies from other British distilleries.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><br />It is this blend that will spearhead the export drive.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><br />A consortium of private investors led by Paul Currie, a co-founder of the Isle of Arran Distillery, is behind the plan to set up a &pound;2.5m distillery on a former farm. It will produce malt whisky, gin and vodka.<br />Mr Currie said: &ldquo;We are well on schedule to start distilling Cumbria&rsquo;s first malt whisky for more than 100 years. We&rsquo;ve also been installing webcams so people can view our progress.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><br />The project includes a visitor centre with bar, bistro and shop. Production is expected to reach 300,000 bottles a year &ndash; although the distillery will have the capacity to produce one million bottles &ndash; and the site should support 27 jobs</p>',131),(56,56,'en','Lakes Distillery Expansion: New Jobs & Major Investment','lakes-distillery-expansion-new-jobs','blog/New__Star_1.jpg','Wednesday, 12th February 2014','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A distillery is set to create and safeguard over 30 jobs after expanding to create a visitor centre, bar and shop.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The expansion of the Lakes Distillery was made possible with a &pound;250,000 investment from Britain&rsquo;s Energy Coast.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The &pound;2million development will be situated at the northern end of lake Bassenthwaite, near Keswick.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><img style=\"float: right; margin-left: 10px; margin-right: 10px; margin-top: 2px; margin-bottom: 2px;\" src=\"/media/files/paul_at_the_one_launch.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"326\" height=\"500\" />Following the launch of its first product, The One blended whisky at Taste Cumbria last Autumn, renovations are now underway at the site with the assistance of the grant from the Government&rsquo;s Regional Growth Fund-supported and Nuclear Decommissioning Authority-backed &lsquo;Investing in Business&rsquo; programme.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The facility will become Cumbria&rsquo;s first whisky distillery for more than a century and is set to become a key attraction for visitors to the County.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Production of The Lakes Gin, The Lakes Vodka and The Lakes Malt is due to start in the summer with the remaining building work complete in time for the visitor centre, bistro, bar and shop to open later in the year.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Paul Currie, Managing Director at Lakes Distillery, said: &ldquo;We&rsquo;re delighted to have secured this award from BEC, which has been essential to support our journey to become a renowned premium whisky producer.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&ldquo;We aspire for The Lakes Distillery to become both a production operation and visitor attraction of excellence to the benefit of the local workforce and economy.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The Investing in Business programme was set up to help businesses looking to create jobs by investing in fixed assets such as buildings, plant and equipment or for research and development.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">It utilises funding from the Government&rsquo;s Regional Growth Fund and a further &pound;1m from the Nuclear Decommissioning Authority.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://www.newsandstar.co.uk/lakes-distillery-expansion-new-jobs-and-major-investment-1.1116315\">News &amp; Star</a></p>',131),(57,57,'en','Celtic Symbols Found At New Lakes Distillery Site','celtic-symbols-found-new-lakes-distillery-site','blog/New__Star_2.jpg','Wednesday, 12th February 2014','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Ancient lucky Celtic symbols have been found at the site of a new distillery.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">More than 20 &lsquo;quatrefoils&rsquo; have been found throughout the buildings at the former Victorian model farm at Bassenthwaite.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Renovation work at the site is set to start this month but managing director of the Lakes Distillery, Paul Currie, said the quatrefoils will be preserved.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&ldquo;We fell in love with the distillery site not just because of its idyllic location and perfect whisky-making conditions, but also because of its character and we have been delighted to discover these symbols of good luck throughout the entire place,&rdquo; he said.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><img style=\"float: right; margin: 5px;\" src=\"/media/files/quatro_2.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"208\" height=\"147\" />&ldquo;They will certainly stand us in good stead over the very busy months to come.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The distillery, the first in Cumbria for over 100 years, will see a &pound;5 million investment programme of work carried out by the summer.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Production of The Lakes Gin and Vodka, and of The Lakes Malt will begin as soon as renovation work completes.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The distillery&rsquo;s visitor centre, which will offer guided tours, a shop and artisan bar and bistro, will open in the autumn.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://www.newsandstar.co.uk/news/business/celtic-symbols-find-at-new-lakes-distillery-site-1.1116266\">News &amp; Star</a></p>',131),(58,58,'en','250,000 To Boost Whisky Jobs','250000-boost-whisky-jobs','blog/Times__Star.jpg','Friday, 14th February 2014','<p>A new whisky distillery near Cockermouth has been given a &pound;250,000 grant to help it create more than 30 jobs.</p>\r\n<p><img style=\"float: right; margin: 5px;\" src=\"/media/files/paul_currie_1.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"320\" height=\"230\" /></p>\r\n<p>The Lakes Distillery, at Setmurthy, has been awarded the cash from Britain&rsquo;s Energy Coast.</p>\r\n<p>It will help the business to unlock a further &pound;2 million of funding.</p>\r\n<p>Renovation work at the former Victorian model farm is set to start this month.</p>\r\n<p>The distillery, the first in Cumbria for more than 100 years, will involve &pound;5 million of work to be carried out by the summer.</p>\r\n<p>Production of a Lakes gin and vodka and Lakes malt whisky will begin as soon as renovation work is completed.</p>\r\n<p>It will also house a visitor centre and bistro, bar and shop in a converted farm at the northern end of Bassenthwaite Lake.</p>\r\n<p>Paul Currie, the distillery&rsquo;s managing director, said: &ldquo;We&rsquo;re delighted to have secured this award, which has been essential to support our journey to become a renowned premium whisky producer.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>Earlier this week workers there found more than 20 quatrefoils &ndash; ancient lucky Celtic symbols &ndash; which the distillery said it will preserve.</p>\r\n<p>A webcam has been installed so people can watch as building work progresses.</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.timesandstar.co.uk/news/people/250-000-to-boost-whisky-jobs-1.1116926\">Times &amp; Star</a></p>',131),(59,59,'en','The ONE for the road....','one-road','blog/TMC_Net.jpg','Saturday, 18th January 2014','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The One is the first ever British blended whisky from the UK\'s newest distillery set in the heart of the picturesque Lake District. But will it be \'the one\'? Jane Hall finds out MANY glasses of amber nectar - otherwise known as whisky - would have been raised to 2014 on New Year\'s Eve.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">But few of the millions toasting the coming year with a glass or two of this magical alcoholic beverage would have had the luxury of doing so with a whisky produced by their own fair hands.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Paul Currie was one such lucky man. As the chimes of Big Ben rang out on the stroke of midnight to signal the start of 2014, the 49- year-old saluted the death of the old and welcomed in the new with a tumbler of The One, the first British blended whisky.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Bringing together whiskies from England, Scotland and Wales, the memorably named The One, is the inaugural drink to come out of Paul\'s new venture, The Lakes Distillery.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">It launched on to the market in the autumn and has thus far been well received by the critics, with one describing the slightly smoky, sweet and fruity drink as a \"really quality blend... crafted with obvious love.\" It bodes well for what is set to be an exciting year ahead for Cumbria\'s first whisky distillery for over a century.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">This spring will see distillation get under way on both a Lakes gin and malt whisky.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">And come the summer, work should be complete on a new visitor centre, bar, bistro and shop at the distillery\'s picturesque headquarters overlooking Bassenthwaite Lake and the shapely ridge of the 3,000-plus foot high Skiddaw.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Once production is in full swing it will see the distillery housed in a secluded former Victorian model farm at Setmurthy seven miles from Keswick, producing up to 400,000 bottles a year each of both the blended and malt whiskies - although afi-cionados will have a few years\' wait before they\'re able to savour the latter.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The Pounds 3m project will ultimately create 30 new jobs and could attract as many as 150,000 visitors a year to an area whose local economy is reliant on tourists attracted by the breath-taking natural beauty.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Paul, living on site in the grand farmhouse just a few steps away from the River Derwent, whose clean and peaty water will play such a vital part in The Lakes Distillery\'s story going forward, has by his own admission a lot to look forward to as he sees plans which have been three years in the making come to fruition.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">He is confident of success, not in a naive, gung-ho way, but borne from the fact that whisky has always been a part of his life - his father was managing director of Chivas-Seagrams\' - and he is a co-founder of The Isle of Arran Distillery set up as recently as 1995.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Paul left that behind to pursue other interests in the spirits world, but it\'s fair to say whisky runs through his veins.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">So it was perhaps inevitable that he would one day open another distillery - although the Lake District wouldn\'t be top of most people\'s list of places to do so.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Whisky, thanks in part to some clever marketing north of the Border, is irrevocably linked to Scotland. But it\'s a drink that can be made any-where, and indeed England did once have its fair share of distilleries. Why they all shut is something of a mystery, but with demand for whisky surging globally (exports have risen by 87% in the last decade and reached Pounds 4.3bn in 2012), there has been a resurgence of distilling south of the River Tweed with businesses opening in East Anglia and London. While some sceptics may scoff at a Lakes\' malt, Paul immediately saw the potential on a family holiday to the area. In terms of scenery and infrastructure, this part of Cumbria shares many qualities with Scotland. Then there is \"the lakes, the peaty foothills, the pure air,\" Paul says. \"I realised this really was perfect whisky country.\" So The Lakes Distillery. - of which he is managing director - was born, although it has been a fairly lengthy gestation; as long as the wait for that first sip of malt will be. It will have to sit in its bourbon and sherry casks for three years - the time it takes under EU law for fermented cereal mash to be recognised as whisky - before being bottled. Paul expects the malt, which he is confidently predicting will have a lightly peated taste, to be \"really good\" at five years plus. Hence the need to start bringing in some cash with The One, the gin and the visitors centre. There have been no shortage of investors willing to back the enterprise, and it turns out there is a strong North East link. The Lakes Distillery\'s chairman is Tyneside-based entrepreneur Nigel Mills, who is heading up the company\'s base in Gosforth, Newcastle. As the main city that Cumbrians look towards, tens of thousands of North Easterners heading to the Lakes every year and the region already emerging as the biggest market for The One, Paul says it made sense for The Lakes Distillery to have its headquarters in Newcastle, leaving the Set Murthy site to get on with whisky production and catering for the hoped for visitors. Nigel will have a hand in this too, however. He owns The Trout Hotel in nearby Cockermouth and will be involved in the bistro and dining side of the centre.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The main hurdle Paul has had to jump was finding the right location. It had to have buildings that could take the stills, scope for development and be close to the right sort of water to provide the base for the malt. And with the Lake District being a National Park and the obvious planning restrictions that go with that, it also had to be a site where the existing structures could be utilised and any development sympathetically undertaken. It was, Paul states, \"very tough. We looked at countless sites and spent days pouring over maps. We got lucky really when we found the model farm.\" He got lucky too when the parish council, DEFRA, Natural England, Cumbria Tourism and the Highways Agency all gave their support. Paul has g at he r e d together an expert team which includes Dr Alan Rutherford, a leading figure in the whisky industry, and master distiller Chris Anderson whose job it will ultimately be to create the perfect blend of grains and malt. There is, after all, only so much that nature can do to help the process. Chris comes from a long line of distinguished Scottish whisky distillers and began his own career at Caolila on Islay. He has also worked at Lagavulin before moving on to Dewars\' distilleries, including Royal Brackla, Aberfeldy, Craigellachie and Aultmore. Whisky, Paul says, \"is oozing through his veins. He brings a wealth of experience to us and he will play the central role in creating the new Lakes Malt.\" They can be \"80% certain\" of how that will taste even before work begins on distillation thanks to the quality of the water and the type of malted barley used. It\'s the other 20% that will remain unknown, which will ultimately give the malt its character and which Chris will guide with his expert hand. Producing The One has been a slightly less painful process. An artisan blend, it is selling well both through The Lakes Distillery. website and at selected independent outlets, and there is hope that it will soon be available in developing markets like Russia, France and Spain. The gin to be made from Lake District botanicals, will hopefully strike a similar chord. Paul says despite the early problems finding a site, there was never any doubt that the distillery would be based in the Lakes. \"In terms of the whisky, you need a location that is the brand, and the great thing about the Lakes is that it\'s known worldwide. And because we are looking at a long-term business it had to have the tourist element and it was very important that we had the bar and bistro. \"With the Keswick area attracting around three million tourists alone a year, we will hopefully have a ready source of visitors we can attract to the bar and bistro and on to the distillery tours. \"Eight per cent of all visitors to Scotland go on a distillery tour, which is amazing, and if we can get a fraction of that interest I will be happy. \" As well as the wonderful location the water is perfect and contains everything necessary for the distilling of the purest whisky.\" With his heart set on the romantic Lakes, Paul never considered basing himself elsewhere. And who can blame him, with Bassenthwaite Lake and the majestic view towards Skiddaw just a few seconds walk from his front door? It\'s a pity that long-awaited first sight and taste of the Lakes Malt will be longer in coming. But patience can be said to be a virtue in many walks of life, and it\'s something that Paul Currie has thankfully acquired over the years. And while there is still a lot of work to do, Paul\'s dream for The Lakes Distillery\'s at last starting to come true. He is optimistic that \"2014 will be a vintage year for us\".Now, that\'s certainly worth raising a glass of \'the water of life\' to. The One is available to buy from www.lakes distillery.com. Prices start from Pounds 3.95 for a 5cl miniature. A 70cl bottle costs Pounds 29.95. The distillery is also offering membership packages.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\'The lakes, the peaty foothills, the pure air; I realised this really was perfect whisky country (c) 2014 ProQuest Information and Learning Company; All Rights Reserved.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://europe.tmcnet.com/news/2014/01/18/7636436.htm\">TMC.net</a></p>',131),(60,60,'en','Whisky distillery secures restoration funding','whisky-distillery-secures-restoration-funding','blog/Place_North_West.jpg','Wednesday, 12th February 2014','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A distillery in Cumbria has secured a &pound;250,000 Investing in Business grant from economic development organisation Britain\'s Energy Coast to unlock a &pound;2m development.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The Lakes Distillery will invest the funding in a new distillery, visitor centre and bistro, bar and shop in a converted Victorian farm at the northern end of Bassenthwaite Lake, near Keswick.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Following the launch of its first product, The One blended whisky at Taste Cumbria last autumn, renovations are now underway at the site. Investing in Business is financed by the Regional Growth Fund and Nuclear Decommissioning Authority.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The new facility will be Cumbria\'s first whisky distillery built for more than a century. Production of The Lakes Gin, The Lakes Vodka and The Lakes Malt is due to start in the summer with the remaining building work complete in time for the visitor centre, bistro, bar and shop to open later in the year.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Paul Currie, managing director of Lakes Distillery, said: \"We aspire for The Lakes Distillery to become both a production operation and visitor attraction of excellence to the benefit of the local workforce and economy.\"</p>',131),(61,61,'en','Lake District Distillery Readies Itself For Production','lake-district-distillery-readies-itslef-production','blog/The_Spirits_Business.jpg','Wednesday, 19th February 2014','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The first distillery to be built in the UK&rsquo;s Lake District in over a century will soon start production after the company received a &pound;250,000 grant.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Artist&rsquo;s impression of The Lakes Distillery &ndash; Cumbria&rsquo;s first distillery in over 100 years</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The Lakes Distillery, which specialises in English whisky, will use the funds to create its site, as well as build a visitors&rsquo; centre, bistro, bar and shop on a Victorian farm near Keswick.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Britain&rsquo;s Energy Coast (BEC) awarded the funds through its &lsquo;Investing in Business&rsquo; grant, enabling the distillery to unlock a further &pound;2 million in investment. A &pound;2.5 development figure was initially confirmed when&nbsp;plans for the new distillery were unveiled last year.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Anticipated to become a &ldquo;key attraction&rdquo; for visitors to Cumbria, The Lakes Distillery is due to start producing its liquid this summer, while its&nbsp;visitors&rsquo; centre, bistro, bar and shop will be open later in the year.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Paul Currie, managing director at Lakes Distillery, said: &ldquo;We&rsquo;re delighted to have secured this award from BEC, which has been essential to support our journey to become a renowned premium whisky producer.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&ldquo;We aspire for The Lakes Distillery to become both a production operation and visitor attraction of excellence to the benefit of the local workforce and economy.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">It was announced in May 2013 that the distillery would launch a&nbsp;<a href=\"/members/founders-club/\">Founders&rsquo; Club to help raise funds for its planned work</a>.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">As part of the plans, consumers were given the chance to own some of The Lakes Distillery&rsquo;s first bottles of whisky, as well as other special offers and discounts, for a one-off payment of &pound;595. The first 100 casks produced each year will also be set aside exclusively for Founders&rsquo; Club members.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The distillery is being built at the edge of Bassenthwaite Lake in the National Park itself. It will contain two stills with a relatively small capacity of 3,500 litres designed to produce a lighter style whisky.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Currie, also co-founder of the Isle Arran Distillery will be joined by former Diageo whisky expert Alan Rutherford, who will oversee production.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Brands to be released by the distillery include The Lakes Gin, The Lakes Vodka and The Lakes Malt.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The Lakes Distillery bottled and released what it claimed was the&nbsp;<a href=\"/brands/one/\">first British blended whisky, called The One</a>, which brings together a range of whiskies from the British Isles.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://www.thespiritsbusiness.com/2014/02/lake-district-distillery-readies-itself-for-production/\">The Spirits Business</a></p>',131),(62,62,'en','New Lakes Distillery To Use Water From River Derwent','new-lakes-distillery-use-water-river-derwent','blog/North_West_Evening_Mail.jpg','Tuesday, 18th February 2014','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Plans to extract water from the River Derwent for a new distillery have been given the green light by the Environment Agency.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Paul Currie, of The Lakes Distillery</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Work is due to get underway this month on The Lakes Distillery, at Bassenthwaite, near Keswick,</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The former Victorian model farm, which will house the first new whisky distillery in Cumbria for over 100 years, is undergoing a multi-million pound redevelopment.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Production of The Lakes Gin and Vodka, and of The Lakes Malt, will begin as soon as renovation is finished, possibly in the spring.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Managing director Paul Currie, co-founder of the Isle of Arran distillery, said they would use the &ldquo;lightly peated&rdquo; water in their Lakes Malt, Lakes Gin and Lakes vodka-brewing process, using a closed loop system to minimise water requirements.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">He said a state-of-the-art treatment plant will also be installed to produce clean water for its visitor centre.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&ldquo;The site will have a biomass boiler for all its heating requirements and will recycle heat during the production process,&rdquo; a spokesman said. &ldquo;Along with this, waste products from the distilling process will be offered to farmers as animal feed and fertiliser.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Production is expected to reach 300,000 bottles a year &ndash; although the distillery will have the capacity to produce 1m bottles &ndash; and the site should support 27 jobs.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Although production has yet to start, The Lakes Distillery launched its first whisky at the Taste Cumbria food event in Cockermouth in September. The One is a blend of grain and malt whiskies from other British distilleries.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Webcams have been installed so people can watch the renovation online. The distillery&rsquo;s visitor centre, which will offer guided tours, a shop and artisan bar and bistro, will open in the autumn.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>',131),(63,63,'en','The ONE is going global...','one-going-glabal','blog/France_Flag.jpg','','<p><span style=\"font-size: medium;\">The ONE is spreading accross Europe, we now have a confirmed distributor in France!</span></p>\r\n<p><img style=\"border: 2px solid black; vertical-align: bottom;\" src=\"/media/files/paris_distributor_.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"567\" height=\"386\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</p>',7),(64,64,'en','Distillery expansion plans to be unveiled at Lake District tourism meeting','distillery-expansion-plans-be-unveiled','blog/Westmorland_Gazette.jpg','Monday, 24th February 2014','<p>First networking event of the year being held for tourist businesses.</p>\r\n<p>LAKES Distillery founder Paul Currie will reveal the company&rsquo;s plans for a visitor centre on the bank of the River Derwent this week.</p>\r\n<p>He has been invited to deliver a presentation&nbsp;on the proposed development during Cumbria Tourism&rsquo;s first commercial members&rsquo; meeting of 2014 at the Skiddaw Hotel, Keswick, on Thursday, from 11am to 1.30pm.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Cumbria Tourism managing director Ian Stephens said: &ldquo;Commercial members&rsquo; meetings are a vital networking opportunity for both our members and the team to get together and share new ideas, keep up to date with key developments in the industry and have the opportunity to raise any issues that are concerning businesses across the county.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>Meanwhile, a team&nbsp;representing the Lake District&rsquo;s leading tourism businesses are planning to set up a stand at the Best of Britain and Ireland Show&nbsp;in Birmingham on March 12 and 13 as part of the build up to English Tourism Week (March 29 - April 6).</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.thewestmorlandgazette.co.uk/news/11032361.Distillery_expansion_plans_to_be_unveiled_at_Lake_District_tourism_meeting/\">Westmorland Gazette</a>&nbsp;</p>',131),(65,65,'en','Renovation work commences at The Lakes Distillery','renovation-work-commences-lakes-distillery','blog/Cumbria_Crack.jpg','Friday, 28th February 2014','<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Renovation work has now commenced at the brand new Lakes Distillery at Setmurthy, near Bassenthwaite in West Cumbria.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">The distillery, the first in Cumbria for over 100 years, will see a multi-million pound investment programme of work over the coming months with completion due by Summer and production of The Lakes Gin, The Lakes Vodka and The Lakes Malt will begin as soon as renovation work comes to an end.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">The distillery&rsquo;s Visitor Centre, which will boast its own artisan bar and bistro, shop and exclusive-use dining room, will open shortly after and is set to become a key attraction for the Lake District.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><img style=\"float: right; margin-left: 10px; margin-right: 10px; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;\" src=\"/media/files/8_medium.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"459\" height=\"306\" />The project has been supported by a &pound;250,000 &lsquo;Investing in Business&rsquo; grant from economic development organisation Britain&rsquo;s Energy Coast. The grant scheme, which is available for fixed assets and land, is supported by funding from the Government&rsquo;s Regional Growth Fund-supported and Nuclear Decommissioning Authority.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Sales of The One, The Lakes Distillery&rsquo;s inaugural product and the very first British blended whisky, have far surpassed expectations proving particularly popular in international export markets and membership for the distillery&rsquo;s exclusive Founders&rsquo; Club and Connoisseurs&rsquo; Club is also in high demand.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Paul Currie, Managing Director of The Lakes Distillery said: &ldquo;It&rsquo;s wonderful to see work at the distillery commence; now we can watch our plans take shape and see years of work come to fruition. This is a very exciting time for West Cumbria, our aim is to become a key attraction and a key employer for the area and we have been delighted at the local support we have received.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">&ldquo;The One is fast establishing itself as an exceptional blended whisky and membership for our Founders&rsquo; Club too is rapidly being taken up as people, particularly Cumbrians, make the most of the opportunity to own a piece of Lake District whisky history.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Brian Hough, Socio Economic Manager for the NDA, which is supporting the Britain&rsquo;s Energy Coast Investing in Business programme, said: &ldquo;It is great to see another shovel enter the ground on a project that is bringing private sector investment and jobs to the local economy. The help and assistance from Britain&rsquo;s Energy Coast, utilising nuclear and Government funding, has been key to making The Lakes Distillery vision a reality and another demonstration of how working together we are making West Cumbria an easier place to invest and grow in.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Web cameras have been installed at the distillery site and people can now view the progress of the renovation work and find out more about The One, the Founders&rsquo; Club and the exclusive Connoisseurs&rsquo; Club, by visiting The Lakes Distillery&rsquo;s website&nbsp;<a href=\"/\" target=\"_blank\">www.lakesdistillery.com</a>.</p>',131),(66,66,'en','Renovation work has now commenced at The Lakes Distillery','renovation-work-has-now-commenced-lakes-distillery','blog/Builder_on_Roof.jpg','The builders have made great progress on the renovation of the roof over the production area of the distillery and the warehouse. ','<p>The builders have made great progress on the renovation of the roof over the production area of the distillery and the warehouse.&nbsp;</p>',7),(67,67,'en','Distillery drinks to success with funding deal','distillery-drinks-success-funding-deal','blog/Insider_Media_1.jpg','Tuesday, 4th March 2014','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Cumbria is to get its first whisky distillery in more than 100 years after a funding deal.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The Lakes Distillery, which is founded by Paul Currie, has received a &pound;250,000 grant from Britain\'s Energy Coast, supported by the Access to Finance Service, to launch the new business.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A total of &pound;2.5m is to be invested in the new site which will be located close to Bassenthwaite Lake. The project will create jobs.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The distillery is to produce <a href=\"/brands/lakes-malt/?preview=1&amp;draft=1&amp;language=en\">malt whisky</a>, <a href=\"/brands/lakes-gin/?preview=1&amp;draft=1&amp;language=en\">gin</a> and <a href=\"/brands/the-lakes-vodka/?preview=1&amp;draft=1&amp;language=en\">vodka</a> for the wholesale market and will also have a visitor centre providing guided tours.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Paul Currie said: \"Malt whisky is a Celtic product, and has been distilled in the highlands and islands of Scotland, in Ireland and in Wales.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\"Now Cumbria, another Celtic region, is to start the age-old skill of whisky distilling once again when we open the doors of The Lakes Distillery. We will be combining long forgotten skills, ingredients, techniques and tradition with our contemporary knowledge and expertise to produce an outstanding range of products.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\"This grant has been fundamental in helping us to achieve our vision of creating a world-class distillery and visitor centre in the area.\"</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Access to Finance advisor Maria Ramsdale said: \"The Lakes Distillery is a fantastic new business and visitor attraction for Cumbria and will be bringing an ancient tradition back to the region.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\"We were delighted to be able to help them to secure the financing they needed to open the distillery and to work alongside the many local investors and supporters already involved in the project.\"</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">David Jones, head of projects, energy and business support at Britain\'s Energy Coast, added: \"With our funding award unlocking a further &pound;7 worth of investment for every &pound;1 we put in, The Lakes Distillery is set to become a real asset to the area.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\"The interest that has already been generated has been a strong indication of future success, which will not only encourage more visitors to the Western Lake District but will be a significant boost to jobs.\"</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Currie previously set up the Arran distillery. The Lakes Distillery launched its first product, The One blended whisky, at Taste Cumbria last autumn.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://www.insidermedia.com/insider/north-west/109591-distillery-drinks-success-funding-deal\">Inside Media</a></p>',131),(68,68,'en','Corporate fun with The Lakes Distillery','corporate-fun-lakes-distillery','blog/Helicopter.jpg','','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">On Friday 7th March&nbsp;The Lakes Distillery team and a group of guests travellled from Newcastle heliport to Armanthwaite Hall on two Dauphins. Paul Currie, managing director and founder of The Lakes Distillery gave a tour around the distillery site while we all enjoyed nibbles provided by Peter Sidwell. We then headed over to the 4* Trout Hotel in Cockermouth for a fantastic lunch.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A great day had by all!!</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>',7),(69,69,'en','Site Visit From Britain\'s Energy Coast','site-visit-britains-energy-coast','blog/Small_Size.jpg','The Lakes Distillery has received a 250,000 grant from Britain\'s Energy Coast, supported by the Access to Finance Service, to launch the new business.\r\n','<p>The Lakes Distillery has received a &pound;250,000 grant from Britain\'s Energy Coast, supported by the Access to Finance Service, to launch the new business.</p>\r\n<p>A total of &pound;2.5m is to be invested in the new site which is located close to Bassenthwaite Lake. Our project will create jobs.</p>',7),(70,70,'en','An exciting visit to Musk','exciting-visit-musk','','Musk are expert providers of brewhouses and distillery equipment, Mash Tuns and Washback systems. They will be creating ','',7),(71,71,'en','Behind the scenes at the photo shoot for our ad campaign','behind-scenes-photo-shoot-our-ad-campaign','blog/IMG_0145.jpg','A peek behind the scenes at our ad campaign shoot. A fantastic day which would not have been possible without the help of Adam and the team at Jules B who dressed and styled the models, as well as shooting the whole day for us!','',7),(72,72,'en','The ONE is en route to France','one-en-route-france','blog/La_Maison_Du_Whisky.jpg','An exciting day at The Lakes Distillery, The ONE is en route to France where we will be stocked in La Maison Du Whisky. \r\n\r\nHave a look behind the scenes at RSM our bottlers in Teesside to see the whisky before it starts its journey. ','<p>An exciting day at The Lakes Distillery, The ONE is en route to France where we will be stocked in La Maison Du Whisky.</p>\r\n<p>Have a look behind the scenes at RSM our bottlers in Teesside to see the whisky before it starts its journey.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<table style=\"height: 225px; width: 330px;\" border=\"0\" align=\"center\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><img src=\"/media/files/picture_006.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></td>\r\n<td><img src=\"/media/files/picture_007.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></td>\r\n<td><img src=\"/media/files/picture_012.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><img src=\"/media/files/picture_013.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></td>\r\n<td><img src=\"/media/files/picture_014.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></td>\r\n<td><img src=\"/media/files/picture_015.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>',7),(73,73,'en','Whisky Sour Bakewell Tart','whisky-sour-bakewell-tart','blog/Bakewell_Tart.jpg','Peter Sidwell cooked up a storm at the Living North Sprig Fair. Follow his recipe to make the perfect Bakwell Tart infused with The ONE whisky. ','<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Peter Sidwell cooked up a storm at the Living North Sprig Fair. Follow his recipe to make the perfect Bakwell Tart infused with The ONE whisky.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<table border=\"0\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Whisky sour bakewell as seen at Living North show</strong>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Pastry</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">250g plain flour&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">125g butter&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">2 egg yolks&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">50g sugar&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Filling</span>&nbsp;<br /><br />150g raisins&nbsp;<br />50ml The One Whisky&nbsp;<br />1 lime juice&nbsp;<br /><br />125g butter&nbsp;<br />125g sugar&nbsp;<br />2 large eggs&nbsp;<br />125g ground almonds&nbsp;<br />1 the zest of one lime&nbsp;<br /><br /><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Method</span>&nbsp;<br /><br />Pour the whisky over the raisins and leave in a bowl to soak&nbsp;<br /><br />Whisk together the egg yolks and sugar until light and fluffy&nbsp;<br />In a desperate bowl rub the flour and butter together to form a bread crumb type texture &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<br />Add the egg mixture to the flour bowl and mix together to form a pastr</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">(add a touch of milk if you need to)&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><br />Leave the pastry to rest in the fridge&nbsp;<br />Meanwhile cream the butter and sugar together until light and fluffy&nbsp;<br />Add in the eggs a little at a time until fully incorporated&nbsp;<br />Add in the lime zest and almonds&nbsp;<br />Fold the mixture together and leave to one side&nbsp;<br /><br />Roll out the pastry and line an 8\" tin&nbsp;<br />Using a hand blended, blend the raisins with the juice of a lime to create a type of jam&nbsp;<br />Spoon the jam into the lined pastry case and spread evenly&nbsp;<br />Top the pastry case with the almond filling and spread out&nbsp;<br /><br />Bake in a pre heated oven at 160c fan for 40-59 minutes&nbsp;<br /><br />To check if it cooked press the middle gently and if it springs back it\'s cooked</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<img style=\"margin-left: 5px; margin-right: 5px; margin-top: 15px; margin-bottom: 15px;\" src=\"/media/files/peter_2.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"450\" height=\"222\" /></p>\r\n<p><img style=\"margin-left: 5px; margin-right: 5px;\" src=\"/media/files/whsiky_infusion.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"450\" height=\"222\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Whisky Infused Raisins</span></strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img style=\"margin-left: 5px; margin-right: 5px;\" src=\"/media/files/squeeze_of_lime.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"450\" height=\"222\" />&nbsp;<strong><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Squeeze of lime</span></strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>',7),(74,74,'en','The Lakes Distillery enjoys huge success at Kendal Festival of Food','lakes-distillery-enjoys-huge-success','blog/Cumbria_Crack_1.jpg','Wednesday, 3rd April 2014','<table border=\"0\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>The Lakes Distillery, Cumbria&rsquo;s first whisky distillery for over 100 years, enjoyed an enormously successful two days at Kendal Festival of Food last weekend, smashing sales targets five times over.</p>\r\n<p>The brand new distillery, located near Bassenthwaite in the Western Lake District, offered samples of its inaugural whisky product &ndash; The One &ndash; throughout the festival and so overwhelming were the sales, supplies almost ran dry and staff had to return to base for additional stock.</p>\r\n<p>The One, an entirely new concept in blended whiskies, is the very first British blended whisky and brings together a range of exceptional whiskies from around the British Isles. Visitors to the festival enjoyed complimentary tastings and The One&rsquo;s perfectly balanced flavour &ndash; slightly smoky, sweet and fruity, nutty, with hints of spice &ndash; proved a huge hit.</p>\r\n<p>Katie Read, Business Development Manager for The Lakes Distillery said: &ldquo;We were blown away by the reaction to The One at Kendal Festival of Food and just can&rsquo;t believe the sales we achieved there &ndash; they far surpassed all our expectations.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;People were just so enthusiastic about both The One and the distillery &ndash; it was heart-warming to have such support. We&rsquo;ve also received an unprecedented amount of enquiries about membership to our Founders&rsquo; Club too, so this was an incredibly fruitful weekend for us.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>The Lakes Distillery&rsquo;s exclusive Founders&rsquo; Club provides a one-off chance to obtain whisky from its first 100 casks of Lakes Malt. Each year for ten years from 2015, members will receive a 70cl bottle of the maturing whisky, forming a rare collection of The Lakes Distillery&rsquo;s first ever production. Membership is strictly limited and already proving popular with local people.</p>\r\n<p>Now exporting The One to seven different countries, The Lakes Distillery is set to start production of The Lakes Malt, The Lakes Gin and The Lakes Vodka this Summer. The distillery site will also boast a state of the art visitor centre, artisan bistro, bar and shop and is aimed to become a key attraction for Cumbria.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><img style=\"float: right; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px; margin-left: 10px; margin-right: 10px;\" src=\"/media/files/paul_at_kendal_food_fest.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"299\" height=\"448\" /></p>\r\n<p><img style=\"float: right; margin-top: 5px; margin-bottom: 5px; margin-left: 10px; margin-right: 10px;\" src=\"/media/files/kendal_food_fest.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"299\" height=\"448\" /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>',131),(75,75,'en','Great success at Kendal Food Festival','great-success-kendal-food-festival','blog/Kendal_Food.jpg','The Lakes Distillery enjoyed an enormously successful two days at Kendal Festival of Food last weekend, smashing sales targets five times over.\r\n\r\n','<p>The Lakes Distillery enjoyed an enormously successful two days at Kendal Festival of Food last weekend, smashing sales targets five times over.</p>\r\n<p>We offered samples of The ONE throughout the festival and so overwhelming were the sales, supplies almost ran dry with us having to return to base for additional stock.</p>\r\n<table border=\"0\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><img src=\"/media/files/paul_at_kendal_food_fest.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"299\" height=\"448\" /></td>\r\n<td><img src=\"/media/files/kendal_food_fest.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"299\" height=\"448\" /></td>\r\n<td><img src=\"/media/files/img_9373.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"299\" height=\"448\" /></td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><img src=\"/media/files/img_7762.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"299\" height=\"448\" /></td>\r\n<td><img src=\"/media/files/img_9419.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"299\" height=\"448\" /></td>\r\n<td><img src=\"/media/files/img_9426.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"299\" height=\"448\" /></td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>',7),(76,76,'en','The One - British blend','one-british-blend','','Sweet aroma, light, fresh Palette, Pear Drops, smooth feel Finish, liquorice, lingering Very nice blend - recommend\r\n','',178),(77,77,'en','Top 10 Whisky Bars in London','top-10-whisky-bars-london','','For many people whisky drinking is a serious business and these London bars offer aficionados the opportunity to indulge in a wide range of drams. ','<p>From restaurants to pubs and hotels to member&rsquo;s clubs there are a number of different venues that cater for different moods and for different types of whisky drinker. These venues also cater to various trends that are seen in the whisky market and offer a wide range of whisky.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<table style=\"width: 195px;\" border=\"0\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>&nbsp;<a href=\"ht